The Prague Stock Exchange fell into the red by the end of trading
After the sharp fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses.
Transactions with ČEZ shares reached almost half of the normal daily trade.
The Prague Stock Exchange followed up on Monday&#39;s drop right from the start of trading on Tuesday, when it fell by almost six percent.
This time, the drop is behind the fall in shares on Wall Street.
Here, too, the market&#39;s reaction to the result of the vote by the US House of Representatives, which refused to support the plan to stabilize the financial sector there, manifests itself.
Stocks fall in Asia
Shares on the stock exchanges in Asia experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although the indices eventually erased some of the losses during the day.
The Hang Seng index of the stock exchange in Hong Kong lost almost four percent during trading, but later erased part of the losses and reduced the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which tracks Chinese shares on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell 3.8 percent, markets were closed in Shanghai.
Shares on the Sydney stock exchange lost more than five percent, but eventually pared losses to 4.3 percent.
The stock market in Taiwan, according to the local index, fell by 3.6 percent.
&quot;The timing of the US bailout is uncertain and will affect financial markets around the world,&quot; said Hong Kong Monetary Authority chief Joseph Yam.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it determines its monetary policy independently, i.e. without dependence on the Chinese central bank.
Hong Kong has interest rates on par with the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US lawmakers should urgently return to negotiations and approve the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries will also feel the effects.
Bloodbath for US stocks
The US House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, which was supposed to cost up to 700 billion dollars (almost 12 trillion CZK).
Lawmakers thus ignored President George W. Bush&#39;s call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
US stocks saw a bloodbath on Monday, with the major stock indexes posting their biggest drop in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell by almost seven percent, the last time it recorded a decline of a similar magnitude in 1987.
The index was already falling before the vote, but once it became clear that the proposal failed in the House, the index found itself in a free fall.
Congress backs down: The US government can pump $700 billion into the banks
Top officials in the US Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader bailout deal for the US financial system.
It will be voted on early next week.
American lawmakers have made a breakthrough in talks on the approval of a rescue plan in the form of financial assistance for the American financial system in the amount of 700 billion dollars (approximately 12 trillion crowns).
However, it has not been won yet.
Congressmen must finalize some details of the agreement before they can publish the final form of the law and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed on the floor of the House of Representatives on Monday.
House Banking and Financial Services Committee Chairman Barney Frank told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, the Senate could probably vote on the plan as early as Wednesday.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be approved should be the first significant psychological factor for the recovery of financial markets.
After that, however, there will be a &quot;sobering&quot; due to the complexity of the mechanisms by which to help the markets achieve this in practice.
Paulson: The plan has to be effective
&quot;We have made great progress.
We&#39;ve resolved our differences on what the market stabilization package should look like,&quot; House Speaker Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could take place on Sunday.
Lawmakers met with US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to finalize the government fund.
He should buy back unsaleable mortgage assets from financial companies, which drag financial companies into heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
&quot;We are on the verge of final agreement on a plan that will work and must also be effective in the market.
We still need to continue with the recovery plan, but I think we&#39;re there,&quot; Paulson said.
Asian trading signal
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are trying to reach a final agreement in Congress on Sunday.
This is because they want to reassure investors before trading on Asian financial markets, which are the first in the time zone where the decision of Congress could affect Monday trading.
However, it is not yet clear with certainty when both houses of the US Congress will vote on the law, or whether the negotiations may stall on some issue at the last minute.
Lawmakers hope to pass it in the next few days.
However, the law will still undergo a number of changes.
The total amount designated for the aid of the system is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be made available as soon as possible, as requested by President George Bush.
But Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it feels that the program is not fulfilling its function, in a sequence of another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush praised the progress in the negotiations
Although the President can veto this decision, Congress can override his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program, which was to raise funds to buy back bad mortgage securities that have fallen in value because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to pay their mortgages, remained intact.
&quot;We worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate on Monday,&quot; said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
US President Bush is also satisfied with the progress in negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said Bush was pleased with Saturday&#39;s progress and appreciated &quot;the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.&quot;
Restrictions on golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the lead negotiator, said lawmakers agreed on accountability for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, closing relief, timing funding for the plan.
The new law is also intended to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the program and establishes a committee that will supervise the fund.
It should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
&quot;We&#39;ve been working very hard on this and we&#39;ve made great progress toward an agreement that will work and be good for the market and good for all Americans,&quot; Paulson said.
The plan also includes help for homeowners who are having trouble making payments.
The government should negotiate new repayments on the mortgages it buys to reduce monthly repayment costs for borrowers and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to Patria Finance Chief Economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its implementation will be very difficult.
&quot;And this is because it is not known by what mechanism and at what price the problem assets will be bought out.
This will determine how the financial sector and the government will share the losses,&quot; Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
According to Mark, whether the plan is approved now or early next week is not that important.
&quot;It is much more important that members of Congress agree this week that they support this plan and that they commit to it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement that there will be approval is the most important at this moment,&quot; Marek emphasized.
The triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, together they have 29 percent
According to the first preliminary results, Sunday&#39;s early parliamentary elections in Austria brought a noticeable weakening of both parties of the previous grand coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties.
The Austrian People&#39;s Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly heavy losses, where the position of the current chairman, Wilhelm Molterer, is seriously shaken.
On the contrary, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Carinthia governor Jörg Haider is preparing a triumphant return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) remains the strongest party in the country with 29.8 percent of the vote, but is losing 5.5 percent of the vote compared to the last election in 2006.
The ÖVP fared even worse, losing almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of both of these major parties in Austria&#39;s post-war history, and especially for the People&#39;s Party, who called for early elections, a literally disastrous result.
Even at the beginning of July, when the ÖVP withdrew from the coalition, the People&#39;s Party had a considerable lead in preferences over the SPÖ.
But the voters apparently punished them for letting the government fail.
Already in the first reactions to the results, there were speculations about the possible resignation of the party chairman and current vice chancellor, Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could happen as early as Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party&#39;s presidency.
Such a development would probably facilitate the path to the most likely way out of the election result, i.e. the restoration of the grand coalition of the SPÖ and the ÖVP.
Due to the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party (FPÖ) preliminarily won 18 percent and the BZÖ eleven percent of the vote - however, the Social Democrats also expressed concern about a repeat of 1999, when the People&#39;s Party agreed with the populists (at that time the FPÖ was still united, in 2005 split from the BZÖ) on the joint government, which even caused sanctions from the European Union.
Haider, who has already declared that he is ready to cooperate with any party and foresees a return to Vienna to national politics, is clearly betting on this development.
The Green Party also entered the parliament, but it lost slightly and fell from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
None of the other parties apparently crossed the four percent threshold and did not get into parliament.
A knife-edge battle: MP3 players versus cell phones.
We will advise you on how to choose
While almost every cell phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
From this it seems clear that it is better to buy just the phone.
Still, there are plenty of reasons to get a stand-alone player.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It&#39;s probably hard to buy a high-end, expensive record player at home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc&#39;s latest album.
On the one hand, such musical products do not appear on LP records, and there is no objective reason for this from a qualitative point of view.
However, if your shelves are crowded with art rock, jazz or blues vinyls, you probably at least dream of such a record player.
It&#39;s the same with music on the go, i.e. compressed music, simply put - music in MP3.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
It may be unacceptable for someone to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan will probably have a hard time trying headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes with plenty of room for everyone.
The selection is wide.
Battery life also matters
Some high-end music players can do a lot more than just play music, but that&#39;s what most mobile phones can&#39;t do.
No current device is as versatile as the telephone.
In addition to the primary functions, calling and texting, it can play music and video, record both, has a better, sometimes worse camera and can even navigate.
And if we consider smartphones and communicators, you will also have a small computer in your pocket.
It&#39;s a small miracle, after all, no refrigerator can grill and no TV can take pictures.
The universality of the mobile phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile, the sooner the indicator on the display will send you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy guzzlers.
Few mobile phones can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
With cheap mobile phones, therefore, expect that they will not play for more than a few hours.
If you still call for it every now and then, get another charger for work just in case - this also applies to more expensive devices.
You won&#39;t have this problem with MP3 players, even the worse ones last at least 9 hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
Another problem occurs when recording music to a mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, and moreover, not all of them can be directly connected to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on a memory card, but only a few card readers can handle the miniature memory cards used in mobile phones without reduction.
With the exception of players (iPod), you do not need any special software.
Just fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players already create their own music library sorted by artist name, album title, genre or even user ratings.
Some devices only display a tree structure of directories similar to Explorer in Windows and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with an operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones are more capable
When choosing a specific device, pay particular attention to battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound output, and, of course, ease of use.
If music is primarily a background for you and you only listen to it briefly every day, for example on the tram, any mobile phone that plays MP3 is enough.
Which almost any mobile phone can do.
You don&#39;t even have to keep track of what music formats your mobile phone or player can handle.
MP3s will handle all of them, and the vast majority of music that will reach you will be in this format.
It is one of the most widespread, and in addition to it, the vast majority of devices can also handle music in WMA format.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
Better mobile phones also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
It is enough to visit the relevant website of the operator (or other provider) via the mobile internet and purchase the song or album.
This service in itself could be a strong argument for the purchase of a music mobile phone.
Unfortunately, the range of operators is poor and mostly limited to fast-release radio hits.
The prices are also not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that this way of selling music (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry a mobile phone with them.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you feel the mobile phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player lies forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you also always carry headphones with you or at least a wired handsfree.
If not, you can use the integrated speaker, which almost every mobile phone has, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music mobiles for many will be the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost under three thousand.
For three or four thousand crowns you can buy a very decent Walkman.
However, you will mostly be limited by the absence of an output for regular headphones.
The best and most technically equipped phones with a 3.5 mm jack for ordinary headphones cost up to fifteen thousand.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, ease of use.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - players can be controlled by anyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity of control with a previously common cassette player or perhaps a gramophone is obvious.
There is no danger of a collision in the form of accidentally switching on the mobile internet and subsequently a huge bill for data transfer.
Which device to reach for
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for removable memory cards (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even with the additional purchase of the relevant card, you can fit within two thousand crowns.
Be careful though.
For basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported.
Only the most expensive ones can handle even 8 GB memory sticks.
If you already have a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, go for Cowon, Creativa, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you don&#39;t have to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, go for specialized mobile phones - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokias and Samsungs).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3 and the comfort of operation is thus close to a separate MP3 player.
The furthest in the industry is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman series mobiles have the same user interface as MP3 players sold separately.
The same service and in the same price range of up to four thousand crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (typically 15 hours, maximum up to 35 hours), will be provided by MP3 players from the aforementioned brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively mature, and our operators offer virtually all services like their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, we are missing something here - a virtual operator that would force the classic ones to be cheaper.
He might not be gone for long.
We have already written many times on Mobil.cz about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
After all, this was also confirmed by the ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the European Commission&#39;s latest steps in the field of regulation of roaming fees, a paradoxical situation may arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really wants to get into the fight.
It may sound paradoxical, after all, we have three mobile networks here and a penetration of well over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to bet on the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák often echoes them, who has stated several times in the past that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It&#39;s probably true that a classic operator with its own network probably doesn&#39;t have much of a chance anymore (after all, it would probably be difficult to find frequencies anymore).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought a significant reduction in prices, to which classic operators had to react as well.
At the same time, even before the entry of pike like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market, voices similar to ours were heard in Great Britain.
But it turned out that there is a place for such operators and they can be really successful.
After all, we don&#39;t have to go too far for examples.
In February of this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
At the same time, behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which in the Czech Republic owns, among other things, U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to operate effectively, they need far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not entail relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators are usually profiled as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, but this is often balanced by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers SMS at least half as cheap as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, a bet on a novel target group can be quite a good move.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
&quot;The right guys choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust,&quot; says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a concept similar to that in Poland could catch on in our country.
Vodafone spokesperson Miroslav Čepický doubts this: &quot;The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings.&quot;
No chance in the Czech Republic, say mobile operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
&quot;We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very promising.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region,&quot; said Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group, in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything so that no potential competitor arises.
The GTS Novera group has not been hiding its interest in launching a virtual mobile operator for a long time, which would like to take the next step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
&quot;We are very interested in being able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunication services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this option with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already managed to make progress in negotiations with some of them,&quot; says the group&#39;s press spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe he&#39;s looking forward to better times.
From unofficial information, it seems that we should see the first virtual operator perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
&quot;At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any entity with a complex and serious project in this area,&quot; said Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2 in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, T-Mobil&#39;s spokesperson, adds, in a rare agreement with O2&#39;s statement: &quot;So far, we have not noticed any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which it would be possible to build on.&quot;
And he adds: &quot;It is unlikely that a virtual operator will appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this moment, we would have to have a concrete agreement on the table in order to be able to think in this short horizon.&quot;
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: &quot;We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
We consider this to be the most beneficial from the customer&#39;s point of view.
Vodafone&#39;s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet.&quot;
Responsible authorities - hand in hand with operators
The progress of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a drop in prices and thus also a drop in their profits.
So why facilitate the entry of such a competitor?
The fact that operators know how to pull together when it comes to something is also evidenced by the tussle surrounding the creation of U:fon.
Probably the biggest pressure towards the ČTÚ came from the T-Mobile company at the time of the creation of U:fon.
This is evidenced by the publicly accessible information from the website of the CTU.
Now, however, U:fon is suitable as an argument for not allowing a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová pointed out: &quot;The competitive environment of the mobile market was recently intensified by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another player would place high demands on it and above all on its services.&quot;
Considering this approach of mobile operators, the complete lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is striking.
At the same time, it is not just about the position of the CTU, which, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic - unlike Great Britain and other developed countries - does not have the authority to intervene in economic competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
But he took his typical stance on the whole issue.
&quot;The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not interesting enough for traditional operators,&quot; said Kristián Chalupa from the department of external relations of the ÚOHS in response to our question.
A statement formulated in this way by representatives of the operators is probably not surprising.
This is more than reasonable from an office that is supposed to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: &quot;Abroad, where virtual operators normally operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the reduction of prices for mobile phone services.&quot;
Apparently, however, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and the drop in prices do not belong to the interests of the ÚOHS.
In truth, what is shocking about the whole case is the touching consensus of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence suggests itself.
Just like the exact same price of gasoline at gas stations, it is surely just the work of chance and fierce competition.
&quot;The authority found no signs of anti-competitive behavior in this matter, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, so they do not have a corresponding increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market for virtual operators are most probably not available to the telecommunications regulator,&quot; Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of market dominance is one of the many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets prepared by the CTU, according to which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
But some legal experts offer a different point of view - the creation of a virtual operator always requires the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - has a monopoly on its network.
So they must necessarily be dominant in a certain segment.
Even if we do not accept this argument, it should at least be a warning for the ÚOHS that the three mobile operators proceed in a strikingly similar way.
At the same time, the complaints of a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when dealing with all operators.
Shifting responsibility to the ČTÚ is then a relatively common trick in telecommunications, with which the ÚOHS gets its hands off the whole matter.
We have already met him in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the extension of the CTU&#39;s powers to the field of economic competition in telecommunications failed to be implemented in the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, although many experts promised an improvement in the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this more than well, but apparently their interests lie elsewhere.
It works when no one is looking
At the same time, the functioning of some pseudo-virtual operators, of which there are quite a few in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies issuing their own price lists for mobile phone services, but they are only partially public.
These are usually companies involved in multilevel marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies are usually only available to a select few.
The magic lies in the fact that the company appears to the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
&quot;If the cases you are talking about occur, it could be a violation of the contractual terms, which we would deal with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company in question,&quot; answered Martina Kemrová to our question about this issue.
But it is quite unlikely that a similar activity would not reach the responsible people from mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
At the same time, none of the operators opposes such a procedure.
They have significant profits from the activities of these companies, and at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - they do not threaten them in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out possible problems: &quot;The law allows such speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
In addition, they have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot dispose of it to the full extent like ordinary customers of mobile operators.&quot;
But that should be at least strange to the CTU.
In addition, another question arises for the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to a similar procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It must be added that the ÚOHS has relatively strong powers to detect similar activity, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the operators&#39; explanation that they have no idea about anything like this and their business conditions prohibit it.
When will we not be the most expensive
As mentioned several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market brought about a noticeable drop in prices for services.
At the same time, in practically all countries where virtual operators were created, classic operators tried to more or less prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were practically identical - too small or too saturated a market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was at these moments that regulatory bodies intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual operator and others flocked to it.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities are tossing the whole case around like a hot potato.
From our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in competences is more than useful for them in these cases.
But let&#39;s not throw a flint in the rye.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and a virtual operator appears in our country really soon, the Czech mobile market may get moving again.
If any of the operators allowed the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will hardly be able to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to four performances of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek ceremonially presented new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov můj on the occasion of Czech Statehood Day.
The anthem was newly recorded by the orchestra of the National Theater under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solo vocals, choral and instrumental versions.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka took over the vocals.
The authors of the adaptations of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to all four versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
He told Czech Radio earlier that he deliberately chose singers with young representative voices who are distinctive and popular to sing the solo versions.
&quot;From the beginning, I tried to make sure that both of them, and then also with the choir, had clear diction, that the text was well understood, that they were in harmony,&quot; he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj was heard for the first time in 1834 on the boards of the Estates Theater in the original Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
She gained popularity and people spontaneously adopted her as their own.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first stanza of the song became a natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
