Sudetenland wanted a referendum after the USA
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans applied for the integration of the Šumava region into the United States.
It follows from the letter, which is kept in the collections of the South Bohemian Science Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we at least want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudeten Germans allegedly approached the US president with such a wish.
This is evident, among other things, from a letter that was preserved in a private archive and today is stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Science Library.
In a letter, the Germans from Český Krumlov ask the American president not to allow the return of the &quot;Šumavska County&quot; - taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - back to Czechoslovakia.
&quot;We understood the situation correctly and we want to be really sure in saying that the American troops are coming to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators,&quot; reads the letter, signed with the words &quot;People who have the fate of Šumava in their hearts.&quot;
Since annexation to Czechoslovakia allegedly gives the Sudeten Germans - knowing the Czech national nature - hope only for brutality, ruthlessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter beg the American president to take over the Šumava as a protectorate for the present and eternal times.
&quot;We cannot believe that, regardless of the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants, you would grant this territory to some foreign state that oppresses and suppresses minorities and has contributed nothing, absolutely nothing to the victory of the Allies,&quot; the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is allegedly the fear of the vindictiveness of the &quot;Czech oppressors&quot;.
If the President of the USA allegedly doubted the mindset of the Šumava Germans, it was enough for him to organize a referendum in the Šumava county on whether its inhabitants wanted to become part of the USA or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound a bit naive with today&#39;s knowledge of post-war history, according to some witnesses, it appropriately illustrates the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at the time.
Even though the Czech Germans must have at least suspected that they would be expelled from the republic, very few of them even considered such a possibility.
Some expected the United States and Great Britain to negotiate some kind of autonomy for the Sudetenland.
Others believed that they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice.
During the war, as a German from Budejovice, he was deployed to the navy in the Baltic.
When he was captured by the British at the end of the war and placed in a POW camp in Holstein, dozens of other Czech Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
&quot;They believed that when they returned home, Czech would be useful to them,&quot; Chalupa said.
According to him, none of the German prisoners living in Czechoslovakia before the war expected to be removed from the republic on the basis of Beneš&#39;s decrees.
