The Czech Republic judges the battle for the seabed
He approaches an electronic wall map showing Australia and the adjacent marine areas.
However, he is not interested in a continent, but a small point lost in the blue of the ocean.
&quot;The island belongs to Australia and with it the adjacent seabed.
At the same time, the area is as big as the continent itself,&quot; says Italian lawyer Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the thirty-member team of workers at the UN Division for Ocean Affairs and the Law of the Sea.
His boss, director of the division, Czech lawyer Václav Mikulka, monitors the interpretation and sometimes adds to it.
There is work ethic and enthusiasm.
The seabed hides a hitherto little-known world, rich in natural resources.
Oil, ores and other mineral resources can be found here, as well as hitherto unknown living organisms, which hold the key to, for example, the development of a cure for cancer.
Bottom larger than land
Today, coastal states have started vehemently bidding for new underwater territories.
According to the UN Convention, they are using their rights, which were agreed upon in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is mainly the area of the so-called continental shelf, which often extends up to several hundred kilometers from the coast of the given country.
According to the convention, it has an exclusive right to all the resources of the continental shelf.
&quot;Simply put, the continental shelf is the part of the seabed and its subsoil that is a natural continuation of the continent under the sea.
It extends beyond the borders of the coastal sea, often even beyond the two hundred nautical miles of the so-called exclusive economic zone&quot;, explains Mikulka.
The request that the country submits to the Commission for the delimitation of the outer limits of the continental shelf must be supported by extensive scientific and technical documentation based on many expensive surveys and measurements.
It is the result of many years of preparatory work.
&quot;One of our tasks is to provide the commission with legal and professional technical assistance.
The commission has so far considered five applications, namely from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far, only the three last-mentioned countries have succeeded,&quot; adds Mikulka.
The success of Australia, which was the first to significantly expand its underwater holdings, has recently received worldwide attention.
But New Zealand also won - the area of the seabed, which the commission admitted to it last week, is about 1.6 million square kilometers, or roughly six times the size of the country itself.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in research.
The profit that will accrue to them in the future from the use of the seabed will, as they promise, be invaluable.
Other states will gradually submit their applications.
They can do so up to ten years after they ratified the &quot;Montego Bay Convention&quot;.
Where the continental shelf ends, the area of the ocean floor begins, declared by the convention to be the &quot;common heritage of mankind&quot;.
No state has an exclusive position here.
The right to mine in this area is granted by an international institution established by the convention.
&quot;But the seabed is no Klondike&quot;, says director Mikulka in exaggeration, saying that its &quot;individual areas are legally clearly defined and their regime contractually anchored&quot;.
Czechs in the Pacific
Part of the seabed today also belongs to the Czech Republic.
They are shared with other states of the former Eastern bloc within the joint organization &quot;Interoceanmetal&quot;.
In 1991, according to the convention, it acquired the status of a so-called &quot;pioneer investor&quot;, just like the investors of a few other states.
It has the right to mine in the ClarionClipperton Zone in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, the Hawaiian Islands and Kiribati.
The area explored by the investor is slightly larger than the former Czechoslovakia.
The bottom is broken there, it is a kind of underwater replica of Tater.
&quot;It is possible to mine there on an area with a total area of 75,000 square kilometers.
The area is a rich deposit of polymetallic concretions containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese,&quot; says another Indian lawyer, Pakshi Rajan.
