Sleepless nights for Hypo Real Estate lenders
Just last week, Federal Finance Minister Peer Steinbrück emphasized that the German banking system is relatively stable.
It&#39;s good that this politician used the word &quot;relatively&quot; and included in his statement the fact that the German banking sector will not be spared from the crisis.
Because that happened last weekend.
Hypo Real Estate (HRE), a Dax-indexed financial house specializing in real estate financing, will receive a multi-billion loan from a consortium of German banks to protect against market turbulence.
A person familiar with the situation told Reuters on Monday that the said loan aid would go up to 35 billion euros.
Interest will have to be paid by Hypo Real Estate (HRE) only on the amount actually spent.
The money is said to come from private and public banks.
In the background are the losses of the Depfa subsidiary.
According to a newspaper report, this state financier refinanced extremely short-term projects for long-term projects for which he lent money, which is now no longer possible due to lack of confidence in the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank&#39;s reserve shrunk by 95% to 2.37 million euros, and the share of equity decreased slightly from 1.6 to 1.45 percent.
Current income and net income from financial transactions fell to zero compared to last year, income from the increased value of receivables and from certain securities as well as from the cancellation of provisions for credit trading fell by more than 70 percent to 5 million euros.
Only thanks to higher income from reimbursements for the subsequent settlement costs during the restructuring of the former Depfa group and from interest compensation according to the tax code and for mediating trade for group companies, the sixteen percent decrease on the income side was still moderate.
The former state financier, after its privatization in 1990, burned out on mortgages for entrepreneurs, which were then separated from the portfolio of services and further managed by Aareal Bank.
Because too little was earned in classical state financing, Depfa became more involved in infrastructure projects and in the financing of joint projects between private investors and the state (Private-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
Hypo Real Estate now has to write off something from the value of its subsidiary, and these write-offs will have a &quot;major material effect&quot; on the profit and loss calculation of the whole group, as some vaguely hinted.
The fact is that there will be no dividend.
Already for 2007, it was shortened by two thirds.
Since taking over Depfa, Hypo Real Estate has been a major financier of state and infrastructure projects.
It depends more heavily than other institutes on refinancing in the interbank market because it has no customer deposits.
