Even rats have feelings
When a rat or cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean they also feel fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux believes that many animals also have feelings.
But how would it be possible to verify that they feel the same when they behave similarly to us?
Contributions of well-known scientists have been published in the Internet magazine &quot;Edge&quot; for several years.
In its series, SPIEGEL ONLINE presents selected answers to the question &quot;What do you consider to be true without being able to prove it?&quot;
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it so far, when we can&#39;t even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case we can at least hope because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, once we start looking at another species and open up the questions of perception or consciousness in general, we enter impenetrable terrain because the hardware doesn&#39;t match.
When in danger, a rat will do what many other animals do: pretend to be dead, run away, or attack.
People behave similarly, from which some scientists infer comparable subjective experiences.
However, I don&#39;t believe in that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
This is partly because the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always involve the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and executive or control functions).
This extensive area is significantly more developed in humans than in other primates, and appears to be completely absent in other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among them knowing who we are and the ability to plan and make decisions, there is reason to believe that humans differ even from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could be hidden in the linguistic nature of man: because so much of his perception is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case we could exclude animals.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly be influenced by language, so animal consciousness, however constructed, would probably differ from most states of our consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to find out what consciousness might look like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor, due to special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, its exploration presents us with great problems.
Most of my conclusions relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more accessible scientifically.
It would be possible to study the processes in animal consciousness regardless of their content, and this is precisely what is done in studies of short-term memory in primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But this approach, pursued by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses on the neural correlates of consciousness rather than the causal mechanisms: the two may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the non-frontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What does this mean for feelings?
I derive them from the fact that the emotional system, such as the fear system, is activated in a brain that is aware of its own activity.
What we refer to as &quot;fear&quot; is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as bodily reactions) makes use of working memory.
Seen from this angle, feelings are closely linked to those areas of the cortex that characterize primates, and humans in particular.
In connection with the naturalness of language, a fine gradation of perception arises, because with the help of words and grammar we can distinguish and categorize states in order to attribute them to others as well as ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in the cortex and brainstem areas devoted to bodily sensations, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brainstem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could easily participate in the feelings perceived by several animal species.
Purely theoretically, I cannot oppose it, however I consider it unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to us as fear in rats and humans is probably felt by both organisms in the same way: But how is it possible to verify, says Pankseep, whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
The cockroach flees from danger - does he feel fear too?
From my point of view, mere similarity of behavior cannot prove the sameness of experience.
Admittedly, the neural comparison takes us further: rats and humans have similar brainstems, whereas cockroaches do not.
But is the brainstem responsible for feelings?
And even if it were possible to prove it in humans: how would we want to prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have feelings.
But I really don&#39;t know how to prove it.
And since their feelings are likely to be fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness rests on special circuits and language), I study emotional behavior rather than emotional perception in rats.
In any case, in this case we can expect progress at the neural level if we measure the same thing in rats and in humans.
As with rats, I don&#39;t examine language and consciousness, I don&#39;t even examine feelings, after all I don&#39;t know if they exist.
It may be considered short-sighted, but I prefer to move forward rather than repeatedly throw myself against the wall.
I am a practical emotionalist.
