One mysterious phenomenon has been perplexing scientists for years - the gravitational slingshot anomaly.
Gravitational sling is a flight maneuver of space probes during which they gain additional momentum in the gravitational field of some space body, for example the Earth.
Thanks to this, the probes can save a lot of fuel.
The European-American Cassini-Huygens probe used this physics trick, as did the Ulysses solar probe.
But what scientists have been saying for years in this case is surprising: flying bodies do not behave 100% as one would expect according to the good old law of gravity.
On the contrary, there are irregularities in the speed.
Probes speed up or slow down unexpectedly.
So far, physicists have not been able to explain this effect.
They christened it the gravitational slingshot anomalies.
Several experts fear that even Albert Einstein&#39;s general theory of relativity, which describes the attraction of matter by the curvature of space, might not be entirely correct.
American physicist Stephen Adler from the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton remains convinced that Einstein was not mistaken, and tries to explain the gravitational slingshot anomaly with the help of the so-called dark matter, the presence of which has been detected by astronomers in the universe.
&quot;Dark matter, which could also be very close to Earth, could be responsible for this anomaly,&quot; he writes.
Space researchers have only known about the existence of dark matter for about ten years.
Evidently, a gravitational force emanates from it, whose effect on other cosmic bodies can be observed.
On the contrary, it itself is completely invisible, which means that it does not emit or reflect any electromagnetic radiation, not even visible light.
According to scientists&#39; calculations, this dark matter makes up a good fifth of the total mass of the universe.
