Turkey&#39;s diplomatic horizons are expanding
Long before Turkey sought to join the European Union, European powers were eager to penetrate deep into Turkish territory.
On the eastern shore of the Bosphorus, perhaps only twenty paces in Asia, stands one of the finest monuments of this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpaša railway station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in the Neo-Renaissance style.
That is what the tourist guides will tell you.
The building sits astride the end of the platforms with a tower at each corner of the facade, looking indistinguishable from some provincial German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole structure is slowly falling apart.
But once inside the vaulted ticket office, one can no longer doubt the size of the enterprise whose westernmost gateway the station was.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a late entrant to the game of empires, intended to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East with the help of this railway, which was to lead to Damascus, Baghdad and beyond to what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany&#39;s imperial ambitions collapsed during the First World War.
Their tracks were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular troops.
The relative isolation from surrounding territories created by the frozen borders of the Cold War is gone
British and colonial troops advanced from Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was also bad news for Hydarpaša station.
In 1917, an ammunition train explosion destroyed its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has gradually crumbled and history has bypassed it.
Today, however, this gateway to Anatolia and further east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - AKP - created a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from surrounding territories created by the frozen borders of the Cold War is gone.
Now a new policy is being implemented - Turkey is getting involved.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
In order to review the parameters of this new policy, I boarded a night train to the Turkish capital, Ankara, to meet with one of the AKP&#39;s leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a bumpy ride on tracks that recalled the old-world rhythms of the famous documentary Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital, designed as a new city for a secular state that wants to turn its back on its Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
She aroused suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi brought me to the AKP&#39;s main tent, an ultra-modern stone and metal building, purpose-built in a burgeoning suburb, surrounded by half-built department stores and powerhouses, where business-suited middle managers - both men and women - meet to do early morning deals. .
Suat Kiniklioglu could easily be a center-right politician from almost any other European political party.
Jacket, tie, I&#39;m sure he had a Blackberry too.
&quot;The goal of the party&#39;s foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate surroundings.
The Cold War was an anomaly,&quot; he told me.
Turkey was cut off from its borders.
Today they have to look east and west at the same time.
It wasn&#39;t a choice.
It had to do both.
&quot;But surely there will come a time,&quot; I asked, &quot;when Turkey may have to make up her mind?&quot;
&quot;Turkey&quot;, he said, &quot;did not wish that such a decision had to take place.&quot;
He then emphasized what almost everyone I spoke to here said almost by heart: Turkey&#39;s relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea region are as much to the benefit of Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, it seems that Europe as a whole can, metaphorically speaking, ride eastward on these tracks to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpaša station, after another mostly awake night, I thought of those two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Cona, who watched this building being built a hundred years ago.
How surprised they would be to learn that Europe&#39;s ambitions in the Middle East may now be, for the most part, in Turkish hands.
And as I waited at the port for the ferry back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that in those days Turkey was called the &quot;sick man of Europe&quot;.
So it seems that, at least then, there was little doubt as to which continent should lay claim to this fascinating land.
