An obscure street, often forgotten and perhaps soon for sale
The city of New York has thousands of roads, streets, highways and other roads, some famous, others only utilitarian.
But even many veteran taxi drivers and longtime locals have trouble finding Extra Place, mostly because they&#39;ve never heard of it.
This tiny alley is in the East Village and runs north from First Street - without going to Second Street - between the Bowery and Second Avenue.
With a width of about ten meters and a length of forty meters, it is more like a dusty passage than a traffic lane.
There are no street name signs.
It is practically invisible in a regular atlas.
Nevertheless, the alley has its admirers.
For example, Avalon Bay, a developer of recently built luxury buildings on First Street.
He wants to repave Extra Place and create a cleaner passage to the shops and boutiques that are to open in the new buildings.
Other admirers include longtime neighbors who say they were charmed by the shortened lane simply because it was one of the last holdovers from before the block was gentrified.
However, the city&#39;s Office for the Protection and Development of Buildings, which has the street in its power, has not the slightest interest in sticking to it.
At a meeting of the community&#39;s land committee, representatives of the municipal authority and the company Avalon Bay outlined a plan according to which the developer should buy the street.
However, according to Suzan Stetzer, District Manager of Community 3, the committee prefers an option where the street remains in the city&#39;s hands, and has requested a new plan that should be submitted next month.
&quot;The city already owns very little land, and we would like Extra Place to remain in its ownership,&quot; she said.
&quot;Proposals could be made for repair and management, which Avalon could do, but we also want to guarantee public accessibility.&quot;
Avalon Bay announced a few months ago that it wanted to repave the small street and add seating, some of which would be used by a cafe, which the developer expects to be interested in leasing the space.
The idea that Avalon Bay could buy the street was first floated at a meeting this month.
Michele de Milly, a spokeswoman for Avalon Bay, said that while the company wants to use the street, it doesn&#39;t necessarily want to own it.
&quot;Avalon Bay&#39;s main intention is to fix this run-down lane and make it a beautiful place for the public,&quot; she said, adding that the sale was proposed by the city.
Seth Donlin, a spokesman for the Preservation Office, said the city did want to sell the street, noting that his office&#39;s job is to develop the property rather than manage it.
Compared to its more colorful neighbor, the Bowery, Extra Place has left a shallow mark on history.
Some people think that the street got its name in 1802 when Philip Minthorn&#39;s large farm was divided among several of his children and the narrow strip of land was unclaimed.
The back door of CBGB, a punk rock landmark that closed in 2006, led to Extra Place, and the alley is perhaps best known as the backdrop to the photo on the cover of the Ramones&#39; &quot;Rocket to Russia&quot; album.
&quot;The place was amazing,&quot; says Ramones manager Danny Fields, who took the photo in November 1976.
&quot;It was full of rubbish, torn clothes and pieces of barrels, posters, leaves and ropes.&quot;
Some locals, including bloggers who write about the gentrification of the East Village, oppose the idea of selling Extra Place, arguing that the piece of public property, however meager, should remain public.
Others consider Extra Place a rarity - an almost unchanged piece of the city that should be left as it is.
Jeremiah Moss, who writes a blog called Jeremiah&#39;s Disappearing New York (subtitled &quot;The Book of Lamentations: A Bitterly Nostalgic Look at a City in the Process of Dying&quot;), posted part of a story about Extra Place from the Let&#39;s Talk About the City column that appeared in The New Yorker in in 1952.
The article&#39;s author, Brendan Gill, wrote: &quot;Extra Place is a narrow cul-de-sac, dark even by day and bordered by rusty iron warehouse doors and boarded-up windows, where week-old newspapers are flung in gutters.&quot;
With a few exceptions, the alley looked exactly the same on a recent evening.
The rat ran across the dead end of the street near the door that once led to CBGB&#39;s, where an expensive clothing store now stands.
There was graffiti on the walls, and an empty beer bottle lay next to a fresh batch of discarded newspapers.
A couple of passers-by said he rarely thought about Extra Place, but suggested he could use a boost.
In contrast, Fields said he thinks some people underestimate the appeal of the alley in its current state.
&quot;The best years of my life,&quot; he said, &quot;were in dark, damp, and foul places.&quot;
The Bilingualism Debate: English Immersion
In this edition of Focus on Education, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi will discuss the candidates&#39; positions on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a Californian scholar and director of education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of &quot;Worse Than You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs School Choice.&quot;
Reaching Hispanic voters effectively is a tricky business.
Barack Obama&#39;s education agenda only proves it.
The Obama campaign notes that &quot;African-American and Hispanic students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,&quot; which is true.
To combat such performance gaps, Obama&#39;s education agenda specifically promotes, among other things, &quot;transitional bilingual education&quot; for English learners.
The question for Barack Obama, however, remains whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes the use of languages other than English in the classroom, is stronger than his interest in narrowing the achievement gap.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, a charter elementary school in East Los Angeles County.
The students of this school are, in the vast majority of cases, Hispanics from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have only recently arrived, are still learning English.
Even so, in the state mathematics tests in 2008, an incredible one hundred percent of fourth graders reached the highest level.
An almost equally amazing ninety-three percent of fourth graders scored at the highest level on the state&#39;s English Language Arts and Literature tests.
This incredible achievement was achieved by a different method than the one preferred by Obama.
Sixth Street emphasizes review and practice, constant assessment of ability, and a no-excuses approach.
Also, and something Obama should take note of, according to Sixth Street principal Linda Mikels, the school&#39;s pedagogic approach for English learners is &quot;total immersion.&quot;
English immersion emphasizes the almost exclusive use of English in teaching.
Miss Mikels, who opposes bilingual education, told me: &quot;We&#39;ve had tremendous success with one brand new pupil from Mexico - after twelve months you&#39;d walk into the classroom and not know which one it is.&quot;
&quot;It works,&quot; she declared, &quot;it works for us.&quot;
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model for what other schools with large proportions of Hispanic and English learners should look like?
The school&#39;s track record should make the answer to that question a foregone conclusion, but his own party&#39;s education agenda (the National Education Association is a longtime supporter of bilingual education) and his own consistent support for bilingual education make it difficult to predict Obama&#39;s answer.
While Obama agrees that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the issue when he said people should stop worrying about &quot;English-only&quot; laws.
Instead, &quot;you should make sure your kids speak Spanish,&quot; he said.
If Obama truly wishes to close the achievement gap, he should think carefully about the educational models that work, rather than mocking and trivializing them.
