With just over three miles to go, Gebreselassie made a final grab and run away from Kwambai, who went on to finish second in 2:05:36, bettering his personal best by almost five minutes.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
In the women&#39;s race, Irina Mikitenkova, a native of Kazakhstan who is now a citizen of Germany, rounded off an excellent year with the seventh fastest time in history, 2:19:19.
The record time of 2:15:25 is held by Paula Radcliffe from Great Britain.
Thirty-six-year-old Mikitenko surprisingly won the London Marathon last spring in 2:24:14.
She missed the Beijing Games with what was described as a back injury, but recovered to win in Berlin, bettering her personal best by almost five minutes in the third marathon she has ever run.
She ran the race smartly and thoughtfully: she let a quartet of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners out to a large lead, then caught them after about 18 ½ miles.
Askale Tafa Magarsa of Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31 and Helene Kiprop of Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
The pride and obstacles of black life in a segregated city
Tucked away among the sprawling theme parks of greater Orlando, a few miles from all the glitz, glitz and glam, lies a quiet town where the pride and grit of African-American life comes alive.
Eatonville, the first all-black town to be incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: &quot;a town of five lakes, three croquet courts, three hundred brownskins, three hundred good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools and no prison.&quot;
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to Eatonville&#39;s annual Zora! festival to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The town she described remains sidelined, even as she made it a tourist stop by including it in a Depression-era Florida travel guide produced by the Federal Writers Project.
It is still as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their true feelings with the white man who &quot;knows so little about us that he doesn&#39;t know what he&#39;s missing.&quot; .&quot;
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidate, Sen. Barack Obama, is calling for an open discussion about race, many residents here remain wary of the views of outsiders.
&quot;We are very careful about how our story is told,&quot; says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the city&#39;s oldest parish.
“It has to be right.
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and toil.
It is both a historic model of Black Ascension and a community of nearly 2,400 people where the poverty rate is double the national average.
It is a center of literature, but also an oak-shaded example of Southern rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes celebrated - that arose out of American slavery.
It&#39;s not too surprising that the people here are both proud and protective.
And the worry about the idea of Eatonville really started with Zora, which is the only way the Hurstons are called here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through heartfelt, dialect-filled books like &quot;Mules and Men&quot; (1935) and &quot;Their Eyes Were Watching God&quot; (1937).
Five paragraphs from a Florida tourist guide turned the town just off Route 17, which runs through the often-overlooked center of Florida, into a stage for black history and human drama.
With the beat of a big drum in life and in literature, Hurston takes the reader into the shop of Eatonville&#39;s first mayor, Joe Clark, and then turns to more personal places.
&quot;On the left by the road,&quot; she wrote, &quot;is a white, brown-trimmed, modern national school with well-kept grounds and playing fields, always attended to by Howard Miller, even though he can&#39;t read or write much.&quot;
She also mentioned Widow Dash&#39;s new husband, writing that Lee Glenn &quot;sells all kinds of drinks and anything else that fits in an hour hotel.&quot;
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
This was clearly not a typical Fodor&#39;s publishing house.
It wasn&#39;t really a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
&quot;Zora told it like it was,&quot; says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson&#39;s choir of girls who immortalized Hurston by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
&quot;Some people didn&#39;t like it,&quot; she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a vivacious eccentric who returned often after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin recalls that most of the time, when she rushed into town, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still prides itself on dressing decently.
Most residents were fascinated, Franklin said, but many scoffed.
&quot;People have always loved seeing Zoro,&quot; Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging in a chair on the back patio overlooking Sabelia Lake, where Hurston was most likely baptized, &quot;she never stayed very long.&quot;
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her along with the rest of the world.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major funerals or large public readings in Eatonville.
&quot;I don&#39;t think they understood her significance to the world or her legacy at all,&quot; said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston&#39;s 2003 biography, &quot;Wrapped in Rainbows.&quot;
Change came in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted a five-lane freeway through the city instead of Kennedy Boulevard, the local two-lane thoroughfare.
Orlando&#39;s sprawl has already pushed Interstate 4 through the city&#39;s western edge.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, among other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950s, the race-mixing battle brought hatred to the doorstep of the community.
&quot;At that time, a bunch of white guys, they came in and threw oranges and stuff at people sitting on the sidelines,&quot; Franklin said.
“We actually had a lady here that was killed by it.
They threw a watermelon from the car.&quot;
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston challenged the Supreme Court&#39;s demand for forced integration, calling its ruling in Brown v. Board of Education &quot;more offensive than glorifying to my race.&quot;
Residents now say that school desegregation, while positive in some areas, has reduced Eatonville&#39;s cohesion and undermined the courage of its youth.
&quot;Black kids were used to hugs — I remember that — you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher at night,&quot; said NY Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
That lasted as long as the teachers and students came from the same place, she added.
&quot;You don&#39;t hug your white teacher because your white teacher - I mean there&#39;s a cultural barrier,&quot; Miss Nathiri said.
Nevertheless, civil rights helped make room for many more Zora Neale Hurstons—black writers, actors, and artists who, like her, rose above prejudice with reckless self-confidence and quotes like, &quot;How can anyone deny me the pleasure of my presence!
I don&#39;t understand that.&quot;
In 1975, Alice Walker traveled to Hurston&#39;s unmarked grave and began fighting to revive her reputation.
Five years later, Robert E. Hemenway&#39;s much-lauded biography of Hurston hit bookstore shelves, reinstating her in the American canon.
The freeway project arrived just as Eatonville&#39;s most famous daughter found the lights on the ramps again.
The Hurstons&#39; former neighbors now saw her as a savior.
To show what could happen to their freeway, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans turned out for the inaugural event two years later, and every January many return to celebrate.
After several years, the state backed away from the highway proposal.
&quot;The five streams of the freeway rekindled, you would say it directly detonated, real civic pride,&quot; Nathiri said.
Boyd put it more simply, &quot;Zora saved Eatonville.&quot;
The victory over the highway project helped change the city&#39;s image.
Out-of-towners like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began attending the local church in 1993, began to show up in greater numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historic Register in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a repaved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes seem like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today it is 90 percent black.)
Strangers who come in search of the story and meaning of Eatonville are still often treated with caution.
Permission must be obtained for most interviews in advance, and certain things - such as the murals in Eatonville&#39;s oldest church, painted by whites and depicting blacks in the fields - cannot be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, a bold, confident teacher who likes deep red, still worry that their isolated community will be misunderstood.
And even as the Hurston festival grew, so did home pride.
Young people in particular tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, troubled and all, but no better, no worse, and just as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish, and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
Franklin&#39;s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, exudes genuine love for the community as he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in local government or on the police force, which he says could use some help.
And even the younger ones, like 11-year-old Winter Park twins Alondra and Alexia Kenon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
&quot;Most people, when they just drive through here, they think, &#39;Hm, this town is nothing against the others,&#39; &quot; Alondra Kenon said after church on a recent Sunday.
&quot;But if you really stop and look at the history for a moment, it&#39;s a very nice town.&quot;
Here in New York, we&#39;re all financially fluent
At first glance, nothing has changed here.
If Manhattan tourists stayed away from the newsstands and giant television screens in Times Square, they wouldn&#39;t realize they were standing in the middle of a storm.
They would never guess that in the glass beehive of offices above their heads, every day the bankers and investment fund managers who monopolize New York are having their worst &quot;bad day at the office&quot; since the Great Depression of 1929.
Delivery men still rattle metal carts down the sidewalks, carrying muffin tins to breakfast meetings.
The Hispanics still move between the towers, carrying, like human mules, fifty ironed shirts that hang from rockers on their backs.
Office rats are still queuing for their morning bagel at street food stalls, and it&#39;s still impossible to get a yellow cab on a weekday between four and seven in the afternoon.
It didn&#39;t seem like a crisis at all until, with all the talk of pessimism, I decided to open a savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Even though I timed this task to coincide with a late afternoon siesta at my local JP Morgan Chase branch, there were already about twenty people waiting in line.
Not in front of teller windows to withdraw or deposit cash, but in front of the counter where older customers order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to Macy&#39;s, and new customers open accounts.
Most of the people before me, I learned from Starr, my &quot;licensed personal banker,&quot; came for the same reason I did.
However, unlike me, they had already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks in the places they came from, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania, or Staten Island.
They took money from so-called thrifts (somewhat similar to building societies), money associations, and those types of savings banks that operate in only one state and that claim to treat their customers like family.
In the past year, 15 such banks quietly went bankrupt.
A few days ago, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, filed for bankruptcy, and as New Yorkers headed home for the weekend Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in assets, was scrambling to hunt down a rescue buyer.
The office and retail workers standing in front of me, fearing another collapse, were moving their cash to a bank that is seen as a safe haven and that does most of the bailing out on Wall Street.
Ordinary New Yorkers have learned financial fluency over the past week.
A woman in my local Chinese supermarket was on the phone talking about Lehman Borthers, that failed bank, and its emaciated chief executive, Dick Fuld, with the familiarity of picking on a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed 50-year-old housekeeper of my apartment building, changed the subject of our usual conversation to Brad, Angelina, or my grocery delivery.
After my visit to the bank, she told me, &quot;I now have my savings in money market funds.
I&#39;ve moved it, I&#39;m not going to risk it.&quot;
Memorable Lives: Vernon Handley and William Woodruff
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford&#39;s music director since 1962, Vernon &quot;Tod&quot; Handley (obituary, September 11) was in charge of the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and Chorus.
As part of the district&#39;s music plan, he founded the excellent youth choir Proteus the following year.
He was supposed to be under 21, but by the time Proteus sang for the last time in 1979, a few of us were almost 30 - we just refused to give up on that choir.
The name &quot;Proteus&quot; (a mythological shape-shifter) represented the choir&#39;s willingness and ability to tackle whatever music was presented to them - be it madrigals or Messiaen, whether alone or with a full orchestra.
The musical adaptability produced by such a young choir was often astonishing, always exciting, all thanks to the inspiration of this one man and a passion for music that remained absolutely unchanged throughout.
How often has Tod told us to &quot;let the music speak for itself&quot;.
He said: &quot;The composer knows what he wants.
It&#39;s all in that music.
So sing it! &quot;
His bar technique was absolutely clear and precise, but it was neither dictatorial nor flowery.
Wherever the musical standard was, he always raised it.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor was to be knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well during the two decades he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
I&#39;ve reviewed over 100 of his concerts over the past 40 years or so, and I can honestly say that I&#39;ve never been disappointed by any of them - and many times I&#39;ve been inspired.
Tod Handley had such a great combination of greatness and personal modesty.
He hated conductors who, in his words, simply &quot;dragged one or two soaked balls around the world&quot;.
He will be missed by many of us.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
Your obituary of William Woodruff (September 25) states that he &quot;returned to economic history at Oxford in 1946 and became a researcher at Houblon-Norman in 1950... while also studying for a BSc, MA and PhD&quot;.
This is based on Woodruff&#39;s author&#39;s note in Beyond Nab End, but it&#39;s not accurate.
From 1946 to 1953 he taught economic history at the University of Nottingham, during which time he completed a dissertation on the British rubber industry supervised by Professor JD Chambers, which he subsequently published in 1958 as the publication British Rubber Industry.
Indeed, he spent the years 1950-51 in America as a researcher at Houblon-Norman and the summer of 1952 at the University of Illinois, Harvard and New York.
In 1953 he left Nottingham for good and moved to Illinois.
It is unknown why Woodruff skipped this part of his career.
Muslim graves desecrated after Austrian right-wing break
Heinz-Christian Strache, left, of the Austrian right-wing Free Party and Filip Dewinter of the Belgian right-wing Vlaams Belang party take part in a demonstration presented by the &quot;Cities Against Islamization&quot; organization in Antwerp on Thursday January 17, 2008.
They carry road sign-like signs that show mosques crossed out with a red line.
Police are accusing right-wing extremists of desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria on the same weekend that far-right parties made huge gains in the general election.
Over 90 graves at a cemetery in the town of Traun, near Linz, were heavily vandalized sometime between Friday evening and this morning, in what police believe was an organized act.
The perpetrators sprayed Jewish symbols such as the Star of David on some of the graves, but detectives believe this may have been an attempt to mask the motives of extremists driven by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is unclear whether this incident was in any way connected to the election.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were &quot;deeply shocked&quot; by reports of the desecration, which comes as the Muslim fasting month of Ramadan draws to a close.
Austria, meanwhile, is entering a round of soul-searching after swinging to the right in yesterday&#39;s parliamentary elections.
The two far-right parties, which together won more than 30 percent of the vote, the Freedom Party and the Union for the Future of Austria, campaigned vehemently against immigration and some of their slogans were condemned as xenophobic by critics.
Heinz-Christian Strache, chairman of the Free Party, which won over 18 percent of the vote, campaigned against headscarves and burkas, and even expressed his opposition to foods perceived to be associated with Islam.
At the last meeting with voters in Vienna, he spoke of &quot;European brotherhood&quot; to prevent the rise of Islam.
Both sides seek to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that they are political symbols of the ongoing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analysis conducted immediately after the election, which put the far right in the position of the strongest political bloc in the country, suggest that the change was mainly caused by young voters who worry about their future in the European Union.
Gary Glitter is not allowed to travel abroad
Gary Glitter, the glam rock star convicted of child sexual abuse, has been banned by a court from traveling to France and Spain.
Officials imposed the six-month ban on Glitter after he informed monitoring authorities that he planned to travel to Spain via France.
Kent Police was granted the travel ban last Thursday after handing officers evidence of Glitter&#39;s past convictions for child sexual abuse.
Glitter, whose real name is Paul Gadd, did not attend the hearing at Ashford Crown Court in Kent but was represented by lawyers from Corker Binning.
A spokesman for the justice service said: &quot;On Thursday 25 September at Ashford Criminal Court, Kent Police applied for an order preventing Mr Paul Gadd from crossing the border into France and Spain until 25 March.
Paul Gadd was not personally involved.&quot;
The 64-year-old Glitter informed authorities that he wished to travel abroad, as required by his record on the sex offender registry.
He must notify the authorities if he wants to travel abroad for more than three days.
They must also give the planned departure date to the police a week in advance.
If he neglected to inform the authorities, he could be sentenced to five years.
Kent Police said it would not be dealing with individual cases of Glitter&#39;s possible travels around the county.
A spokeswoman for Kent Police said: &quot;Kent Police will do everything necessary to protect children in this country or abroad.
From our perspective, it is easier to track someone who remains in Britain because we have extensive systems here to manage potential dangers more effectively.
Protecting the people of Kent is a top priority for Kent Police and we work closely to monitor the behavior of recorded sex offenders to minimize any danger to the public.&quot;
Glitter returned to Britain last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for abusing two girls aged 10 and 11.
When he was released, he flew to Bangkok to catch a flight to London.
But he said he was not feeling well and refused to fly to London.
The Thai authorities did not let him go through passport control and he eventually flew to Hong Kong.
Chinese authorities also refused him entry and he flew back to Bangkok, where Thai police and immigration officials insisted he return to Britain.
He eventually arrived at Heathrow&#39;s Terminal 3 on 22 August and remained there while his solicitor David Corker went to Uxbridge Magistrates&#39; Court in West London, while Scotland Yard successfully sought an order requiring him to register as a sex offender.
Glitter was previously jailed for four months in the UK for possessing child pornography.
A Home Office source said Jacqui Smith, the Home Secretary, was relieved and pleased Glitter had been prevented from traveling to France and Spain.
“To capture the true character, I photograph the master offstage. Günther Bauer - photographer
No heels, no frills or costumes.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, detached from concentration on interpretation - that&#39;s the only way I can achieve a relaxed expression of a man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the second - a person.
Inseparable, if we leave aside privacy, in those moments far from the audience - then one can see a confidential gesture, the depth of a fleeting glance or a passionate gesticulation of hands that are carefree because they are not going to take the stage.
In &quot;Flamenco-people&quot; the German Günther Bauer alternates the theatricality of performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with the lesser-known face of the masters.
With this intention, the photographer compiles a unique flamenco iconography from various environments.
The exhibition, which takes place as part of the program of the Month of Flamenco Photography (Mes de la Fotografía Flamenca), &quot;reflects the ever-increasing international importance of flamenco&quot;, says the author, explaining that &quot;Flamenco-people&quot; &quot;can be any people, but if you look at the photographs , you will find that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people portrayed &quot;on the street&quot; are artists capable of transferring passion, sadness, joy... and completely captivating the audience.
It is not necessary to take pictures on stage to capture the personality of these artists.
They carry their personality and character inside.
I was interested in creating a relaxed atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the flamenco greats.
Fascinated by the &quot;Cante de las Minas&quot; festival, in 1997 Bauer began a long journey of portraits of flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers on a plate camera.
They are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, resemble classic photography.
The use of different stylistic devices contradicts the classical basis of the film and lends it a contemporary spirit, an idea that, according to Bauer himself, is also mirrored by flamenco: &quot;Music with very traditional roots, but which never ceases to surprise and evolve.&quot;
What captivates the audience is not the action of the dance, song or play itself, but the personality and character of the performer.
The search for the moment when we meet the most essential, with that spirit that manifests itself in the way of perception, being and experiencing, that was and is the constant of the work presented during these days in the El Fotómata gallery.
This selection of almost seventy photographed artists is made up of well-known flamenco figures, such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyosová, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales and Vicente Amigo.
The project has become a kind of anthology of flamenco and will soon see a book edition, which will include the exhibited portraits.
The passion for portraiture led Bauer two years ago to the idea of repeating the idea on &quot;Portraits of sports veterans&quot; (&quot;SportARTproject&quot;).
Although their concept is different from &quot;Flamenco-people&quot;, the photographer admits that &quot;photographing people, getting to know them and having the opportunity to enter their lives for a moment, whether long or short - that&#39;s my passion.
I think portraiture is the most difficult genre in photography.
One meets or encounters people, personalities that one does not even know at times, or they only give him a few minutes to take photos.
Despite similar circumstances, as a photographer I always try to realize my ideas.&quot;
A collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco called &quot;Flamenco-people&quot; is exhibited at El Fotómata Gallery at 20 de la Mata street, parallel to Alameda de Hércules, and can be visited until October 16.
Vargas Llosa admitted that the novel he is writing is a &quot;dare&quot;
It takes place in an environment he does not yet know and tells about events unknown to him, yet Mario Vargas Llosa intends to successfully implement his new project - he is currently working on a novel whose main character is Roger Casemant, an Irish nationalist who lived in the Congo for twenty years and he also traveled in the Amazon.
The perennial favorite for the Nobel Prize for Literature admitted yesterday at Segovia&#39;s Hay Festival that the project he is currently working on &quot;is an audacity&quot; and that &quot;everything indicates that I shouldn&#39;t be writing&quot; the novel.
&quot;If I had sense, I wouldn&#39;t do it, but I will do it and I believe I will finish it one day,&quot; he concluded his contribution at the festival of the exchange of ideas, thoughts and words, which during four days saw around a hundred writers, historians and journalists in the city of Aqueduct and thousands of other people.
The author of the novel &quot;City and Dogs&quot; was one of the main characters of the third year of the Word Festival and he lived up to expectations.
Vargas Llosa, who won the Hay Festival prize for the most popular writer - an old edition of Dickens&#39; &quot;Our mutual friend&quot; - filled the Juan Bravo Theater to capacity.
With Félix Romeo introducing him, he had a dedicated audience in front of him, for whom an hour of time flew by like water - the Peruvian recalled with amazing accuracy and a considerable dose of humor how in him from the original &quot;incredible adventure&quot; to &quot;the pleasure of an avid reader&quot; and &quot;to be able to live more than I lived&quot; gave birth to a literary mission; how he makes up for the &quot;lack of inspiration&quot; by writing &quot;disciplinedly&quot;, carefully collecting the text, correcting and rewriting; or how Faulkner, Victor Hugo and Alexandre Dumas influenced his writing and what &quot;memory images&quot; are the supporting basis of his stories.
The Hispanic-American novelist admitted that &quot;there is no way&quot; to find out if and to what extent books can change a life, &quot;but I refuse to believe that literature is just entertainment, a fleeting experience&quot; - emphasized Vargas Llosa, saying that, according to him, &quot;on people acts&quot; and &quot;makes them try to get out of line&quot;, and urged writers to &quot;not be frivolous&quot; and &quot;take responsibility&quot; for their mission.
