Isabel Bayón revives the spiritual legacy of the Sevillian dancer Tórtola Valencia
A Sevillian flamenco dancer pays tribute to another Sevillian dancer.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia, to a Catalan father (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and an Andalusian mother (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the Triana district and moved with her family to London when she was three years old.
She danced modern dance and focused on oriental dances.
She lived a life full of passion, she was a pioneer of female emancipation like Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and a vegetarian and fought for the abolition of the corset, which prevented women from moving freely.
The life of this woman, influenced by the dance and aesthetic revolution of interwar Europe, enchanted Isabela Bayón.
&quot;I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she suggested this character to me - I thought it was incredible.&quot;
According to the dancer, &quot;we are not about telling her life, but about capturing her soul.
The names of her dance performances reminded me of flamenco rhythms.
So &quot;butterfly dance&quot; evoked a guajira or &quot;snake dance&quot; some kind of tango.
Her dance was sensual and they told me that my dance also corresponds to this aesthetic,&quot; she claims.
The performance counts on the involvement of two exceptional personalities: Miguel Poveda, who will sing Isabele in one performance as in &quot;The Open Door&quot; (La puerta abierta), and dance teacher Matilde Coralová, who made an exception and agreed to collaborate with her former student.
&quot;Matilde represents the older Tórtola, a mature character.
I am happy that she accepted the offer to participate in my project, and it is a great honor for me.&quot;
The performance also features the music and guitars of Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, with the singing of Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; the drums of El Pájar, the viola of Raf El Viola and the collaboration of the actor Juanfra Juárez, &quot;who has the role of eternal guide of this kind of female artists who are prima donnas with everything and who are always in love with them&quot;.
The work also takes into account the life of this woman, which took place at the time in places as far away as India, the United States or Russia, as well as throughout Europe, as she usually resided in London.
&quot;I wanted to commemorate her because I think she was one of those women who at a certain time had a huge influence, but today no one knows her and even less appreciates her work,&quot; says Bayónová.
The performance starts today at 20.30 at the Lope de Vega theater.
