Honda attacks for the second time with its bestseller
In the month of November, Honda will start selling the second generation of the Jazz model.
If the predecessor of this single-compartment vehicle already had considerable space, it now offers an even more spacious interior.
This is joined by improved engines that increase driving comfort and enable greater fuel economy.
Evolution rather than revolution.
This is the second generation Honda Jazz.
Although from an aesthetic point of view, the lines of the new Jazz are very similar to the previous model, there have been many changes to this sedan.
It should be mentioned, for example, the innovative design, new platform, larger dimensions and new engines.
Even before we examine the new model, it should be noted that the new Jazz comes to the market six years after the launch of the first generation.
Therefore, the first thing we notice is the fact that Honda needed a shorter period than other manufacturers to rejuvenate this model.
Although the Jazz is a lesser-known model in Europe, it has become a sales phenomenon in other markets.
Such is the case in Japan, the country where the Jazz was the best-selling car in 2002 and also during this year, 2008.
It was in Japan that almost a million units of the Honda Jazz were sold since its launch.
The second market became the old continent, with approximately half a million units sold in six years.
However, Honda aims for the new Jazz to increase sales in its category.
Thus, while in 2007 this Japanese company sold a total of 83,000 units of the Honda Jazz, in 2009 estimates count for 100,000 cars, which would mean an increase of 17% on the European market.
Regarding the Spanish market, Honda has sold a total of 8,000 units of the Jazz since 2002, representing 6.7% of Honda&#39;s total sales in Spain.
As for the new generation of Jazz, the management of the Spanish branch expects to sell 2,000 units for the whole year.
It is the arrival of the new Jazz that will allow Honda to significantly mitigate the decline in sales in Spain.
The management of the car company thus de facto expects the end of the year with a total number of 22,000 units sold, which means 4,000 less than in 2007 and a decrease of 16%.
Despite this increase in sales, Honda increased its share of the Spanish market to 1.8%, up from 1.6% last year.
In 2010, this Japanese company expects to reach 2%.
Honda is banking on the success of its next new model to achieve that share.
It is the Honda Insight, a five-door compact hybrid with a length of 4.37 meters, of which the Japanese company promises to sell approximately 200,000 units per year worldwide.
In terms of markets, the Japanese manufacturer estimates that 50% of the Insight will be sold in the United States, while the remaining percentages will be split between the old continent and Japan.
The Honda Insight is expected to go on sale in the first months of next year, once it is unveiled to the public in Valencia in January.
Compared to the first generation, all dimensions of the new Jazz have increased.
Its length has increased to 3.9 meters (five centimeters more), width to 1.69 meters (two centimeters more) and wheelbase to 2.5 meters, which means an extension of five centimeters.
The height, on the other hand, has not changed and is still 1.52 meters.
The increase in dimensions also increased the interior space.
This advantage was achieved both by using a new platform and by storing the fuel tank in the middle of the car, which was already used in the previous Honda Jazz.
The volume of the luggage compartment - which features a double bottom system - has also increased to 399 litres, 19 liters more than the volume of the luggage compartment of the first generation.
It should be noted that these dimensions are found in the version with the 1.4 engine, since the volume of the luggage compartment in the Honda Jazz 1.2 is 379 liters.
Another improvement in addition to external elements - such as rear LED lights or the option of equipping with a glass panoramic roof - is easier access to the rear seats.
The doors leading to the second row of seats allow an opening angle of 80 degrees, compared to 67 in the first model Jazz.
The second generation Honda Jazz also has new engines.
Initially, this small model will be offered with two petrol engines of 1.2 and 1.4 liters.
Both engines use i-VTEC technology, which enables lower fuel consumption, lower CO2 emissions and delivers excellent powertrain refinement while delivering high torque throughout the engine&#39;s rev range.
The first 1.2-liter engine produces 90 hp at 6,000 rpm with a maximum torque of 114 Nm at 4,900 rpm.
This engine - which had 78 horsepower in the previous generation Jazz - has a consumption of 5.3 liters and emissions of 125 grams of CO2.
Compared to the previous engine, which reached 83 horsepower in the previous generation, the current one will reach 100.
Honda Jazz 1.4 with 100 horsepower has a combined consumption of 5.4 liters and emissions of 128 grams of CO2.
