&quot;Auto bee&quot; prevents collisions
This time, Nissan took inspiration from nature, specifically bees, to advance the development of accident-preventing technologies.
This Japanese company has created a robot that imitates the flight of bees and thus avoids collisions.
Such is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which represents the first step in collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at the Center for Technical Advancement of Nissan Motor Co. the robot was developed in cooperation with the Center for Advancement in Scientific and Technological Research of the prestigious Japanese University of Tokyo.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the brand&#39;s general manager of public relations for technology, research and development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan&#39;s four-zone safety shield.
The robot&#39;s task is to strengthen the collision prevention ability of cars of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, very similar to the safety shield of a Nissan.
But most important are the bee&#39;s compound eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees, which allows the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
In creating this visual feature, engineers designed what they called a Laser Range Finder.
It detects obstacles up to two meters within a 180-degree radius in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it into a collision warning.
&quot;The moment an obstacle is detected, the robot imitates the bee&#39;s movements and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to a right angle or even more to avoid a collision.
The biggest difference to any existing system is the fact that all evasive maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If it wasn&#39;t, the robot wouldn&#39;t be able to react fast enough to avoid obstacles,&quot; explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot move up and down or diagonally, its movement is limited to only two dimensions and to the direction in which it is enabled by turning its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities as with bees.
Therefore, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, Nissan also used the rotation function to prevent the robot from colliding.
&quot;The device only needs to process information every few seconds and behave according to this data.
It does not require the retention of information or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, allowing it to operate without interruption with only two dozen KB of memory.
It might surprise you, but we&#39;re not talking about giga or mega memory.&quot;
This is the first step in the development of new technologies for immediate collision prevention, technology that Nissan predicts will be used in production cars in a decade.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future use of this technology could be the incorporation of a unit into the GPS satellite navigation system, which would guide the driver to the destination while avoiding obstacles on the way.
Drivers repeatedly caught with alcohol in their blood will have to install an &quot;alcolock&quot;
The Ministry of the Interior requires that a driver with three administrative penalties for driving under the influence of alcohol must install a system in his car that prevents him from starting the car while drunk or if he is not breathing.
The proposal became known already in June of this year and is now already included in the annual report of the Supreme State Attorney&#39;s Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last one year.
Its goal is to get drivers back behind the wheel, so drivers will also have to complete a traffic re-education course.
In addition to the National Office for Transport Safety, the Directorate General of Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Technological Institute for Automobile Safety (FITSA) will also participate in this experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75% of motorists charged more than once for driving while intoxicated will get behind the wheel again in this state.
Alcolock should prevent this, as it is a system attached to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not take a breath first or if a higher than permitted alcohol concentration is detected.
Its price exceeds 1,000 euros and the culprit would have to pay it himself.
A study conducted in the USA in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device had a 65% reduction in offenses within the first year of implementation.
In Spain, it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people every year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address this behavior before it results in a criminal offence.
And in order to help its introduction, because the legal regulation can be carried out in the usual way, however, the necessary regulation of criminal provisions requires an amendment to the law.
The device is not yet available in any sales version on the Spanish market, although it has already been trial installed in some industrial and public service vehicles.
