Sleep talking
Some children talk at night.
I don&#39;t mean the ones who wake up and eagerly tell us something that happened the day before, but the children who talk while they sleep.
It might startle you the first time it happens, but it&#39;s actually insignificant.
This is a harmless sleep disorder called somniloquia.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I&#39;m sure many of you have been told that he talked in his sleep at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (for example, once in a lifetime during high fevers), or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once every few months...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is not just one reason that would explain its onset.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, night rages, enuresis nocturna (wetting at night) or sleepwalking, but this may not be the case.
As mentioned earlier, it can often be accompanied by very high fevers, stressful or agitated situations.
In any case, this is an understudied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also different.
The child can speak in a calm voice, say single words, whisper, or just the opposite (screams, cries, long speeches...).
In cases where it manifests itself with great force, it would be advisable to observe the child and consult a specialist to find out if he has some problem that causes him great anxiety and manifests in this way.
We said that this is a harmless disorder, therefore it is not treated, only if it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with apnea syndrome or permanent stress).
What we can do, however, is to keep in mind a few very simple precautions, such as:
Try not to disturb the child too much before he goes to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid scary or somewhat violent TV programs or series.
For very nervous children and those who find it difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner peace.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
When somniloquy occurs, try to stay calm.
Remind yourself that it is harmless to the child and that he will not remember anything about what happened the next day.
Helpful hints
Don&#39;t be him.
It&#39;s pointless because he&#39;s not conscious and you&#39;re interrupting his sleep.
Even when he is talking, he is sleeping and therefore resting.
Remember that if it seems to you several times in a row that he is very worried, it would be advisable to seek advice or to find out what is causing such anxiety in the child.
If you can understand what he is saying (which is not so common), avoid the temptation to interrogate him and extract information from him.
It won&#39;t do any good because when he&#39;s asleep he&#39;s not conscious enough to organize his thoughts.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he dreams about, and therefore why he says it, so be very careful how you interpret the information and what conclusions you draw.
Never tell your child that you can ask him about his secrets at night.
Not even for fun.
This causes great anxiety.
Just don&#39;t worry, it&#39;s nothing bad, it&#39;s just an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
