Interview - Blood that is sure again
Héma-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday and its president, dr. Francine Décary, rightly rejoiced, as Héma-Québec became one of the most reliable and efficient suppliers of blood in the world.
Above all, he has regained the public&#39;s trust, which was seriously shaken after the contaminated blood scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, the national blood pool managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Division was contaminated with human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In light of this drama and a wave of public outrage, the Canadian government launched a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to formulate recommendations to prevent such a disaster from happening again.
While Judge Krever delayed submitting his report, several provinces launched a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee played this role.
Following the Gélineau and Krever report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec, to serve Québec, and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all provinces and both territories.
&quot;When Héma-Québec started its activities in 1998, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system,&quot; recalls Dr. Décary.
&quot;The situation was dire.
Through continuous efforts to increase the safety of blood products and constant work in this area over the following years, we regained the public&#39;s trust,&quot; he says, proudly adding that at the beginning of 2008, Héma-Québec was already trusted by almost 94% of the Quebec population.
Dr. However, Décary does not lose sight of the fact that &quot;trust is something very fragile&quot;.
Since its foundation on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the principle of prudence.
&quot;At that time in Europe we witnessed many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease,&quot; says the woman who has led the company since its founding in 1998.
&quot;And we had no idea if this disease could spread through blood.
We therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau report, according to which, in the case when we do not know and when the spread of a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration that inevitably leads to death, it is need to take exclusionary measures.
In April 1999 we therefore refused blood from people who had been in the UK for more than one month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that this disease is transmitted through blood.
So this episode showed us that sticking to the precautionary principle made sense.&quot;
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting the HIV virus appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (NAT), which make it possible to detect the presence of the virus itself in donor blood directly, and not the presence of antibodies, on which the tests used before were based.
NAT tests made it possible to shorten the silent period that occurs between the moment a patient is infected and the moment when our techniques can detect the first viruses in the blood, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period to less than a week.
In this way, we have significantly reduced the risk that some donors could be infected without knowing it and without being able to figure it out.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of acquiring AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
&quot;In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone becomes infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take 24 years before the first case of HIV transmission through a blood product occurs.
I believe that today we can receive or prescribe the blood transfusion necessary for recovery in complete peace,&quot; says the head of the Héma-Québec management.
&quot;The challenge for us for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what disease-causing element may appear in the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood through an insect bite.
You have to be constantly cautious,&quot; continues Dr. Décaryová, emphasizing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also count on a sufficient supply.
&quot;The needs are increasing because the population is aging.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population also has implications for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of Quebecers eligible to donate.&quot;
Any healthy person at least 18 years old, meeting the admissibility criteria, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is six times a year.
14% of people offering blood are not accepted on average because they are carriers of AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have visited a country where mud fever runs rampant, they are excluded for a year.
&quot;With this 3%, we can maintain a state that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
However, the members of the donor network need to be replenished in proportion to how old they are and can no longer donate blood.
However, persuading people to donate blood is difficult, especially retaining and motivating them to become regular donors.
Today&#39;s life is so unfettered that we rarely find an hour to donate blood,&quot; laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, such as bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
Umbilical cord, once considered biomedical waste, is rich in stem cell-rich blood that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
&quot;We celebrated depositing our 1,000th cord blood sample into the bank a few weeks ago and expect to collect over a thousand a year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants,&quot; explains Dr. Décaryová, who describes the umbilical cord blood collection program as very popular.
&quot;Some moms are disappointed that they don&#39;t have access to it,&quot; because Héma-Québec doesn&#39;t have enough resources to offer this complex and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
