Opinions - Barrick Gold&#39;s Orwellian discourse
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir printed a letter from Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, he confirms that the world&#39;s largest gold producer has launched a libel suit against three authors and a poor little publisher in order to provoke a &quot;transparent public debate&quot; and demands six million from them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge truth, especially in libel prosecutions, but the law.
Not surprisingly, Garver completely misses this crucial distinction.
Or is the best way for Barrick Gold to lead a public debate, to bankrupt anyone who dares to take a contrary position?
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of Noir Canada will be forced to spend considerable sums to be prepared to defend themselves and fight a very uneven battle with an army of lawyers backed by the almost bottomless pockets of the mining company.
After all, the tactic in these lopsided battles often consists of ruining the defendants in order to force a settlement that silences the other party and terrifies anyone who dares to pursue the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, they should have presented their view of the matter to the public.
Contrary to what happens in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada the debate normally consists of an exchange of ideas, not blows with a baton.
Therefore, it was not enough for the mining companies to open their books, their documentation and create a real debate through newspapers, media, publications and funding of independent scientific teams that could shed light on the whole matter.
However, Barrick Gold seems to have no faith in public opinion and is dismissing petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand &quot;public debate&quot; and at the same time despise the views of the same public?
In the Vice President&#39;s world, the word seems to refer only to high-paid lawyers, not all Canadians; this is a rather narrow understanding of the term.
In a democracy, even rioters have the right to speak.
Barrick Gold doesn&#39;t understand - or doesn&#39;t want to understand - that the public who support the authors and publishers of Noir Canada do so primarily because they reject the brutal ways of the mining company.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and judge the matter, but through a civilized exchange of arguments, not in what many perceive as a gagging prosecution (as part of its &quot;public debate&quot; prosecution, by the way, Barrick just filed a formal summons to the authors of Noir Canada to give them official notice that they should stop using the term...).
Garver&#39;s surreal speech aside, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the university&#39;s freedom of inquiry and truth-seeking, which are fundamental to any democratic society.
Overall, it denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate the facts and interpretations that constitute the very basis of intellectual activity.
If it is going to be impossible in a country like Canada to study and discuss topics that the rich corporations of this world don&#39;t like without exposing ourselves to repeated prosecutions, who else will be able to do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could have created one if it had followed the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
He has a right to reply.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold&#39;s overblown lawsuit makes it clear that, despite what it claims, it has no desire to have a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place measures to curb this type of wrongful prosecution.
