Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a socially engaged icon
His beauty with azure eyes has long been his trump card, according to others his weakness.
Has this American actor with the charming smile broken out of narcissism?
Yes and no.
The shyness, sensitivity and relentless talent inherent in him also distanced him from the power category that breeds true stars.
But what a long-distance runner he was!
Paul Newman died on Friday at the age of 83 at his ranch in Connecticut as a result of lung cancer and remains one of the last icons of the fat years of American cinema.
Less spectacular than Brando, whom he resembled and had long been a kind of rival on the screen, Newman was a more cautious actor, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the breakdown of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often produces beautiful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, his father was a German Jew and his mother was Hungarian.
From these European roots was born one of the famous faces of the American dream.
Without excessive ego, which is the last sign of quality.
Because he saw this whole country in love with a self-made man, a Pacific War veteran, battle-wounded, who studied acting at Yale in the early 1950s, then attended New York&#39;s Actor&#39;s Studio and triumphed in the theater, on television, and soon in movie.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also a race car driver who finished second in the 24 Hours of Le Mans in 1979 and a sex symbol, despite being a model couple with actress Joanne Woodward from 1958 .
With him also go the shady places of this hidden, discreet, socially engaged star, allergic to the fuss of his own show business, which will forever remain somewhat mysterious.
A decent man, in the noblest sense of the word.
Paul Newman&#39;s passing this weekend sent film buffs into a tizzy as his big roles jostle on the black screen of memories.
After him parades more than half a century of constantly changing American seventh art.
The charming cowboy from Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), the young man who rejects his voluptuous wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in Cat on a Hot Roof, Tennessee Williams&#39; 1958 adaptation, resurfaces in memory.
From the not-so-distant past (1990), we recall his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled in his advanced age by a marriage that did not meet all expectations.
So many other Paul Newmans went down in history.
Boxer Rocky Graziano, the battered, violent, unforgettable delinquent of Robert Wise&#39;s Somebody Up There Likes Me, a role intended for James Dean, taken over after his death, which in 1956 introduced Newman to real fame.
Sympathetic gangster in the absolutely brilliant The Sting (Podraz), Oscar for best film in 1973.
A bitter and vengeful pool player in Robert Rossen&#39;s wonderful The Hustler (1961), he would portray the same character in Martin Scorsese&#39;s The Color of Money, which would earn him his only Oscar out of seven nominations in 1987.
This face wandering through the ages, that was him.
And him again.
Different eras compete with each other in his professional career.
Young people know him mainly thanks to George Roy Hill&#39;s iconic Slap Shot (1977) in the role of Reggie Dunlop, an unconventional hockey coach.
Fans met him again in 1994 in the Coen brothers&#39; The Hudsucker Proxy.
He then closed his career with the role of the godfather of the Irish mafia in Sam Mendes&#39; Road to Perdition in 2003.
Unlike several film legends who left the craft relatively early, Newman stayed in the industry for a long time, though he decried Hollywood with its glitz, pomp and concessions.
The French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered him, not without humor, &quot;a living challenge of underplaying&quot;, judging that he pressed the saw too much in his performances.
For the handsome Paul Newman, to whom roles came like on a platter, the profession was not always so gentle.
However, he played first lovers less often than outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, rascals and despairers, whose decline and rebellion were reflected in his perfect features.
As a director, Newman revealed little-known sides of his shy sensibility.
His 1968 film Rachel, Rachel (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), in which his wife Joanne Woodward played the leading role, gives a sensitive female portrait filled with melancholy.
He dedicated the 1984 film Harry and Son, a work full of shame and sadness, to his son Scott, who he lost to an overdose.
