What was produced in the Zuschlag &amp; Co. invoice factory?
Soon, on October 8, the trial in the criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his associates will begin.
In addition to other crimes, including forgery of documents, the politician and his associates are accused of fraud perpetrated for a long time and systematically by a criminal organization, as a result of which extremely significant damages were caused.
According to the prosecutor&#39;s office, they used money obtained in public tenders for their own purposes and often documented the fulfillment of tasks with fictitious invoices.
Money from the state and municipalities - a total of approximately 65 million forints - went partly to the treasury of the Fiatal Baloldal organization, partly to the pockets of individuals.
The method, which was also reported by the investigating office, consisted in the fact that the money obtained in public tenders was collected on the basis of invoices for which there was no real consideration, and the associations never lived up to the accepted obligations.
According to the indictment, a large part of the invoices were fake.
The forms for these invoices came from the Józsefváros market, the round stamps were made in Kiskunhalasi.
It was decided, among other things, on the circular trip along the northern shore of Lake Balaton, on which István Lados was sent by János Zuschlag.
According to his testimony, the first-named should have checked out guesthouses and restaurants.
In them, he asked for bills for his consumption, based on which invoices were then produced in the framework of public tenders issued by, among others, the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs, and the Self-Government of the capital city.
The invoices were mostly issued by István Lados with his partner András Őri, who, according to our information, most often wrote the reports needed to obtain subsidies.
During his &quot;study trip&quot;, Lados spotted a pub.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and his associates in 2003, this hospitality establishment provided meals for a ninety-member group from the Biztos Pont association.
However, according to the company manager, this facility could not fit so many people at once.
Likewise, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to a foundation called Jobb Jövőért, later Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért, was full of formal and content errors.
The guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj only had three rooms, no more than ten people could sleep in it one night, yet one hundred and thirty guests were listed on the invoice.
Fillers of the forms with a rich imagination, however, went too far even when they included a company also engaged in the hospitality industry - Pigal s.r.o., in whose accounting, according to the information provided to the public prosecutor&#39;s office, the documents bearing the names of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá did not even appear.
The head of the company, Győző Farkas, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor&#39;s office and shown the invoices, he immediately knew that they were fake documents.
&quot;Our business name and tax number were in the wrong place on the stamp.&quot;
As he added, in addition to the formalities, they also disagreed with the fact that according to the invoice they accommodated one hundred people, because they only have eleven rooms, which do not have such a large capacity.
In addition, the invoice also indicated catering, while their restaurant has been out of business for a long time.
The zealous invoice producers were not even convinced that the chosen Budapest travel agency only organizes foreign trips, and on the invoice with payment in cash, which also did not match the company&#39;s invoicing practice, they foolishly listed it as a Hungarian travel agency service.
In addition, as it emerged during the investigation, they also stated VAT in the document, although the organization of trips to countries outside the European Union was exempt from VAT.
Among other things, the company Hotel Révfülöp s.r.o. did not agree on the amount of VAT on the four documents presented to the Jobb Jövőért foundation. The company&#39;s activities are not subject to the mentioned 25 percent VAT, but rather 15 percent, in addition, the hotel employees issued only printed invoices, but the invoice produced was handwritten.
In addition, the &quot;publishers&quot; spoiled the invoice, for example, by stating that for one company, as it became clear thanks to the investigation of the public prosecutor&#39;s office, as a performed activity, the road transport of goods, which the company originally based on investment consulting, did not perform.
The fact that the invoices issued to the Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért Foundation and the associations XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont fake, it also failed because of formal deviations - mismatched invoice format and fake stamp.
As in the case of the Ravenna ks company or the Sports Camp in Kunfehértó, whose representatives denied that they issued the invoices.
For example, the forgers did not even notice that the company HIB s.r.o. from Nyíregyháza was in liquidation at the time (2001), when a group from the Fiatal Városért association ate at it, which is why, according to our information, the liquidation commissioner of the company also denied that he had issued the paper .
They issued invoices knowingly
The second group of invoicers consists of those who knew they had to issue a fictitious invoice.
The Esély Budapestért Foundation issued invoices for around four million forints for the Harmadik Évezredért Foundation at the request of the organization Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták.
According to the indictment, one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi, forced the manager of Collab s.r.o. to issue a fictitious account.
The company Biogate sr o, currently in liquidation, also cooperated with Zuschlag and his associates, which in 2003 supplied the Jobb Jövőért foundation and the Atlasz and Vörösfenyő associations with invoices worth approximately five million forints, which were not backed by real economic activity.
Nor the movement of money, because the created invoices were later canceled, which the organizations forgot to mention in their documents.
Another group of invoicing companies includes those that had ties to the defendants.
For example, Iván Kubatov was the authorized representative of the Ukrainian executive of Delta Trió s.r.o., dealing in fuel and motor vehicle trading, based in Budapest, but the company cannot be found there.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment worth approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the data found by the investigation, these invoices were bought by the Kiskunhala company Cash Investment s.r.o., which was in liquidation since September 14, 2005.
The manager of this company was a man from Romania, to whom Iván Kubatov was also supposed to hand over documents relating to the company in the years 2002-2005.
As we know, Kubatov admitted during the investigation that on behalf of the company he issued invoices to the Atlasz, Hoppá associations and the Együtt and Harmadik Évezredért foundations and himself accepted their consideration.
Expressly at the request of Iván Kubatov, Romanian masons founded the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari s.r.o. and Jos-Investment ks
In fact, however, none of the companies worked, according to the defendant, because they did not get work.
Nevertheless, the companies benefited him, because at the request of the co-accused lawyer Zsolt Szente, who also prepared their articles of incorporation, he issued invoices on behalf of the companies to the associations Atlasz and Y-Generáció connected to Zuschlag.
On behalf of the companies Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, Kubatov gave the organizations a total of 15 invoices worth HUF 14.2 million.
The State Prosecutor&#39;s Office concluded that Kubatov had earned 10 percent of the amounts stated on the invoices and VAT.
The man also used the company Szi-Beri kt to issue fictitious invoices, this time for a tender for the Biztos Pont association
In January 2006, Y-Generáció and Szötségét and Modern Magyarországért submitted proposals to the public tender of the Mihály Táncsics Foundation (TMA), a public benefit organization of the Socialist Party.
They received 500,000 forints each, but did not spend the amounts on the goals stated in the proposals.
In order not to reveal it, TMA submitted five fictitious invoices from the company Works Team s.r.o
After all, these invoices were found during a house search in Árpád Kemecsei&#39;s office at the Ministry of Education.
During the trial, some of the defendants will probably describe the process of producing the invoices, as they already did at the prosecutor&#39;s office.
It might be more interesting if the main defendant János Zuschlag himself decides to reveal everything.
His statement so far is not very detailed, and although he has promised several times to explain everything in detail, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest - in exchange for paying a large part of the damage, fifty million forints, maybe the socialists made a deal with him and Zusi will take it upon himself.
After all, he could still be offended, because his requests to ease the conditions of his detention, namely to place him under house arrest, have so far gone unheeded.
While perpetrators of economic crimes who have caused much greater damage that they have not yet paid can walk around freely or at least wait for the end of the proceedings against them in their homes, he does not have this option.
The psychology of trumping: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money and overprice goods.
Neurological and economic foundations of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior were discovered by researchers from the field of neurology and economics at New York University.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people don&#39;t want to fall behind in a competition like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
Using an experimental auction, the research attempted to map the scheme of this &quot;game&quot; in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group participated in a game auction, while the active areas of the subjects&#39; brains were examined using the method of functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
In both games, the participants could win money, but in the auction game, an important element of which is to trump the other side, a unit located under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, began to work intensively when losing.
Among many other functions, this brain region plays a role in the &quot;self-rewarding&quot; mechanism of the nervous system.
According to the researchers, the screwing up of the price can therefore be explained by an attempt to avoid a violent reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, members of the research team of economists conducted a financial cross-sectional survey.
In it, three groups bid against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was simply told what the fair value of the product was and they placed bets.
In addition, members of another group were promised that if they emerged victorious from the game, they would receive another $15 as a reward.
The third group, on the other hand, received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also received this money.
Thus, the difference between the two groups basically consisted in the fact that one emphasized winning and the other emphasized losing.
However, the members of the &quot;against losing&quot; group were willing to go higher than the control and &quot;winning&quot; groups, which confirms the neuroscientists&#39; hypothesis.
&quot;These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
Until now, they explained the phenomena observed at auctions by the joy of winning and avoiding risks.
It was only neuroimaging methods that helped us resolve the contradiction between these two theories so that we now arrive at a third explanation,&quot; said Andrew Schotter, a professor at NYU&#39;s School of Economics.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are treated. The reason for this is that the sick often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a collective name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the causative agents of the disease and the diseases caused by them differ from each other.
Depending on the causative agents of the disease, hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways: hepatitis types A and E through the digestive system (for example, infected food, water), hepatitis types B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (semen, vaginal secretions, saliva) .
Travelers should in any case protect themselves by vaccination against virus A and B, there is no vaccine against virus type C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected food, they are usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal discomfort, the urge to vomit.
After that, the skin and the whites of the eyes become jaundiced, the stools become lighter and the urine becomes darker. Treatment can last two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people worldwide die from a more serious form of the disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that, according to estimates, only every tenth infected person is treated with medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most of the infected do not even know about their disease, the causative agent of the disease destroys the liver cells insidiously, so the first symptoms do not appear in many cases until 20-30 years later.
Therefore, early prevention and regular screening is very important.
In three groups, the disease occurs much more often than average: among people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, among drug users, and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C virus worldwide is 200 million.
Since the disease can already be proven by a routine laboratory examination, a person should contact his general practitioner if he notices any symptom of unknown origin.
If detected early, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, thus preventing contagion and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized worldwide in 2004 by organizations representing patients.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of its occurrence and the importance of early recognition of the disease.
The Benelux governments will nationalize the Fortis bank
The Benelux countries will help the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was the first in Europe to get into trouble due to the spreading effect of the US mortgage market crisis, with a partial nationalization: the three countries will support the money and insurance institution, which also has a capital participation in Hungary, with the amount of 11.2 billion euros.
