Who believes in god, doesn&#39;t it hurt so much?
According to the results of recent research, faith in God works as a certain analgesic that could ease the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists from the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment, investigating how belief in God affects the perception of pain in humans, the British newspaper Telegraph reported.
In a rather bizarre study, they subjected 12 Catholic believers and an equal number of atheists to electric shocks while they all observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to eliminate a large part of the pain.
Thanks to a technique that examines the human brain in detail, it was also shown that the Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
The research is the first in a series of investigations in which, in addition to academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university are participating.
The test was carried out precisely in such a way that they attached a sparking device that emitted electric shocks to the left hand of the test subject.
The researchers asked participants to gaze intently at two paintings: Sassoferrato&#39;s Virgin Mary from the 17th century and Leonardo da Vinci&#39;s Lady with an Ermine, painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the research hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would induce a certain state of piety in the believers, while they chose da Vinci&#39;s painting because it is not too different from the first one and has a calming effect, according to them.
Subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, during which time they received 20 electric shocks in four consecutive parts, while separately viewing an image with a religious or general theme.
Catholics reported that looking at the Virgin Mary made them feel &quot;safe&quot;, as if they were &quot;taken care of&quot; and &quot;calmed, filled with peace&quot;.
According to their statement, they felt 12 percent less pain when viewing a painting with a religious theme than when they had Leonardo&#39;s work in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also took part in the research, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any powerfully impressive image even with atheists, you just need to find the right photo.
&quot;We would have to find an image that they will perceive very positively, from the position of a mother or a father,&quot; said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
&quot;The practice of faith should change, and in many cases will change, our personality,&quot; added Wright.
After such great results, the only question is what effect it would have on the pain regulation of the faithful if they were shown a Madonna by Leonardo or a painter of similar caliber.
Would looking at a quality Virgin Mary mean achieving even better results?
You are what you share of yourself
On its tenth birthday, Google can claim that people can find it in their pocket at least as well as in the sky overhead; they know where they were on vacation, what professional examinations they attend and what they are interested in.
However, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the heads of the company, this is still not enough.
However, as for the skeptics who draw parallels with Orwell&#39;s dark vision, the very nature of Web 2.0 is not clear to them.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google&#39;s main goal is to collect even more personal data about users, which is necessary in order for the founders of Google to stick to their original intention, which was: &quot;Let&#39;s organize all the information in the world!&quot;
According to the interviewed representative of Google, even after ten years of groundbreaking work, the company is only at the beginning of being able to work with all information.
When asked what it will be like in five years, Schmidt said that he would like Google to be able to answer questions like &quot;what should I do tomorrow?&quot; or &quot;what job would actually be suitable for me?&quot; - however, the software will not be able to answer such seemingly simple questions until they know enough information about the users.
Not all Internet users are well aware that during an Internet search, the searched words are accurately recorded, as well as the IP address from which the search was made and to which pages the interested party moved after the search.
Thanks to the Personalized Search service launched two years ago, users can, for example, keep their surfing history, look back at what they searched for and what they clicked on, thanks to which, in the long term, results are generated that are much more tailored to them - the same logic will be based on and the Recommendations service, through which the system will offer us products and services based on previously stated and saved preferences.
What if my data is used against me, what if someone looks at what I&#39;m up to? - ask users who are afraid of Google&#39;s data monopoly.
In most cases, the extent of the potential power represented by the company has a threatening effect, the backlash does not evoke in Internet users a sense of guilt, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or even rebellion against power.
However, it is a confirmed fact that all search terms are not only captured, but in justified cases can also be released to a third party, in such legal cases the personal rights of Internet users are not protected.
The best-known recent example was probably the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google provided the Brazilian government with information that enabled the identification of pedophiles from the Orkut community site, set up through it.
However, Internet users who are worried about personal rights could still breathe a sigh of relief in May, when the company hand in hand with the organization for the protection of electronic rights EFF successfully proved its truth in the dispute with the FBI: Google may not be forced by any article of the constitution in the future. to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully seized nearly fifty thousand web addresses and a thousand search terms, which it obtained citing the strengthening of the Child Protection Act passed years ago, but was unable to obtain individual user search lists, or complete lists of websites and keywords covering a period of two months.)
The opinion of Google is thus quite contradictory: it is whipped by those who are afraid of providing their personal data, because they feel that their intimate sphere and private life will be exposed to harm by starting to use Google services, and they oppose it with a revolt like belongs to multinational companies with a conservative image.
And so far, the American geek culture and its wild offshoot, grouping around itself enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users, appearing in many countries, see in it a new generation of large companies, &quot;a corporation that is now snarling&quot;, in contrast to its rival Microsoft, considered because of Windows as the conqueror of the world, even though both are fighting for the same goals.
This may be due to the fact that, unlike Microsoft, Google does not require an identification code from its users and does not ask them to pay for its applications; an open, free and constantly fresh source of information and a package of programs feels much more accessible, more youthful, &quot;cooler&quot; than the practice of the official software giant.
But it may also be due to the fact that geeks accurately understand the very problematic relationship between the Internet and personal rights, which has brought with it precisely one of the most popular keywords of recent years: web 2.0.
After all, Web 2.0 is about nothing but collaboration, about intentionally leaving traces behind and using the communication channels available to us, and although the extent of these is different for everyone, the essence remains the same: we show up.
The average young person can maintain a profile on several community sites, from Facebook to Xanga, which he can easily connect to other services, for example, Twitter or the last.fm application, recording the music he listens to, all of which he can then connect to navigation systems, such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, in addition, he can write a blog, where his latest photo galleries, which he saves on Flickr or Picasa, will automatically appear.
At the same time, we can read about a lot of exemplary cases from which it shines: in the morning, a girlfriend, looking at a flood of photos of mutual friends, can easily figure out who her naughty boyfriend spent the evening with, or a company can fire an employee just because he describes his an honest opinion about senior management: one thing is certain, the concept of private life has been completely re-evaluated today.
The one who lives an online life consists of what he shows of himself, so we could define the basic thesis behind the behavior of today&#39;s youth.
And anyone who wants to hide something or at least avoid the Google monopoly has the option (starting with Scroogle, for example, who uses the Google search system, but intentionally leaves no traces).
For example, a significant number of people deliberately do not register on community sites so that they cannot be found. Google&#39;s online applications, from a text editor to a photo editor and a news portal, can be exchanged for alternative versions that are not connected to giant server parks and that do not build the best possible profile of us.
Public opinion is not-so-secretly waiting for Google to show its teeth.
With a current value of $156 billion, the business is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising space threatens advertising agency investment and services are being rolled out at an ever-accelerating pace they seriously make life difficult not only for Microsoft but also for numerous other software designers.
However, critical observers also find disturbing counterpoints: for example, the senior management completely rejected the protests of the employees after it doubled the fee for the company nursery school, the employees&#39; frequent daily meals were too expensive according to the company management, but all this is lost beside the fact, that Google bowed to the Chinese government back in 2006 and, in terms of their agreement, will filter out every finding that goes against the good taste or the interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the company&#39;s internal rules is that it never advertises new services in advance, only when they can already be used, but what is certain is that the expected problems of the coming months and years may move the world in new places: while some believe that Google&#39;s project aimed at for scanning and archiving books and magazines is taking on such dimensions that the company will soon have to deal with the US Supreme Court, others are afraid of its Health system, because in it we can compile a complete personal health profile with previous findings, doctors and problems.
The fact that Google compiles a genetic database can then serve as good starting material for the following generations of science fiction writers, Cory Doctorow&#39;s famous novel &quot;Scroogled&quot; describes with Orwellian reminiscences a future in which one can get frighteningly close to a person only with the help of data from google.
