A smart car imitates the flight of a bumblebee
So what would be the best method of developing collision avoidance technologies if not to imitate obstacle detectors found in the natural world?
For example in bees.
The initial strategic idea of the surprising project, presented at the Japanese CEATEC trade fair, was inspired by bumblebees to engineers from the Nissan company. It was about how to build a new generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has constructed the BR23C Biomimetic Robotic Driving System, a robotic minicar that is equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
&quot;During flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety protective envelope,&quot; Kazuhiro Doi, the brand&#39;s general manager of technology PR and R&amp;D, explained at the show.
An important role is played by compound eyes, which allow bees to see in all directions with a visual angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the compound eye, engineers reached for the idea of a laser range finder.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 meters in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into an operation aimed at avoiding a collision.
The obstacle is caught in a fraction of a second, after which the robotic car begins to imitate the movements of the bee, turning the wheels to the extent necessary to avoid a collision, and immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this evasive maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive manner.
&quot;If this were not the case, the robot car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,&quot; explains Toshiyuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the Robot Car Project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology conforms to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety protective envelope, within which a collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must mirror what the bee is doing to avoid other bees.
This process should not take more than the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed up, down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be turned.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to the bees when dodging, in the case of the robotic car only the possibility of rotating movement, acceleration and deceleration was applied.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they last longer than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, what is important is an instinctive, intelligent response, not the ability to process, much less store, data.
This mechanism must process and respond to only a few incoming signals per second.
It doesn&#39;t need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it only uses a few kilobytes of memory at all times.
It does not need memory with a gigabyte or megabyte capacity.
It&#39;s the first step in developing the instant-avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates could be in production cars within a decade.
Another possibility of application can be the connection of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the motorist to the specified final destination after avoiding obstacles in the way.
The damn precious baby already has a name
The law on the economic rescue package worth 700 billion dollars, which is to be divided into several installments and which aims to buy out bad loans of banks, is already in writing.
Half of the amount will be used in the first round.
After further negotiations that ended just after midnight EST on Saturday, congressional officials reached an agreement in several days of debate on a bailout package worth a total of $700 billion, Reuters reported.
&quot;We&#39;ve made significant progress,&quot; said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic speaker of the House of Representatives, who said the only thing left to do was write the deal.
Both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain also supported the package compromise.
Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson said of the outcome of the compromise: &quot;The program will work and be effective, but more steps need to be taken.&quot;
The written form of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets on Sunday at 8:00 pm Washington time (that is, on Monday at 2:00 am Central European time), but it did not cause any particular rise in the stock exchanges.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will first vote on the draft legal standard called the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008, which is to establish the program, then it will be the Senate&#39;s turn.
President George W. Bush spoke with Pelosi on Saturday night, after which news of the deal was also welcomed at the White House.
&quot;We are pleased with the progress made overnight and greatly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy,&quot; White House spokesman Tony Fratto said.
After all, the program differs from the Bush administration&#39;s original proposal, in which the entire sum of $700 billion was to be spent at once on the purchase of low-quality mortgage-backed securities.
Now, up to half of the $700 billion can be spent in the first round, with $250 billion to be used immediately after Congress decides on the matter, expected on Monday, and used by the Treasury Department to buy mortgage-backed securities rated as poor quality, the fate of the remaining $100 billion will then depend on the president&#39;s decision.
The program will be overseen by a special board, which will also include the chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank.
Spending the second half of the $700 billion will depend on the next decision of Congress.
According to the law, the Ministry of Finance can use a combined tactic: it can simultaneously buy back bad loans, mortgages and securities secured by mortgages, or other &quot;toxic&quot; loans.
The purchase can take place within the framework of auctions or directly, informed the competent representatives of the ministry.
The legal norm will allow the companies in question to participate in an insurance program in which the Ministry of Finance will provide them with a guarantee for funds representing a cause for concern, for which the company will then pay a price corresponding to the amount of expected damages.
As Henry Paulson said, the law provides the necessary funds to spend up to $700 billion to meet the urgent needs of the American financial system, whether it is a large-scale purchase of bad assets, to insure them or to prevent the systemic risk associated with the collapse of one of the big financial institutions.
&quot;We will take the necessary steps to be ready to implement the law as soon as it is signed,&quot; he added.
Heads of banks that have got into trouble and are waiting for state aid, on the other hand, can count on the government to reduce their severance pay - which in overseas slang is simply called a &quot;golden parachute&quot;.
Their payments will be restricted only in certain cases, moreover, these restrictions will depend on the type of assistance provided by the Ministry.
The restriction basically means that if the ministry buys in the auction, there will be a tax surcharge on the golden parachutes, unless the fallen bank directors are sent straight into retirement.
In the case of direct buyouts of non-performing loans, the government will act aggressively to ensure that the money for management is not excessive.
It should be added that the already existing golden parachute contracts will not change, the restriction applies only to new contracts, which should be an additional incentive to participate in the program.
&quot;This is the first time in American history that there will be a statutory cap on CEO compensation,&quot; House Financial Services Committee Chairman Barney Frank, a Democrat, commented on the provision.
In addition, the state will have the right to obtain a share in the banks participating in the program, which will reduce the risk for taxpayers, because once the economy and with it the rescued bank get back on their feet, they can also make money from this transaction.
The plan of the proposal includes that in the next five years, the president must submit a proposal to Congress setting out how the expected losses from the financial sector can be returned to taxpayers.
Of course, there were voices on both sides expressing doubts about the plan.
&quot;This is not what the American people asked for, this is not going to protect taxpayer dollars,&quot; said California Republican Congressman Darrell Issa.
His fellow Democrat from Ohio, Mary Kaptur, believes that the very people responsible for the collapse of Wall Street pushed for the provision.
