Fox in the henhouse
Life and health insurance companies in America often reject the possibility of concluding an insurance contract with an applicant based on people&#39;s drug purchase data.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become out of control.
&quot;There is a data protection program that binds the use of prescription data to the consent of the individual in each case.
It has to be in the hands of someone independent, otherwise we&#39;re handing over the hen house to the fox,&quot; the Washington Post quoted Richard Dick, author of the prescription drug monitoring program, as saying.
Insurance companies make insurance premiums and amounts paid out in case of insured events dependent on the health status of the interested parties, and if the risk is evaluated as too great, they will not even take out insurance with him.
Previously, they sent the persons concerned for medical examinations and concluded the contract only when they knew the results.
Ten years ago, Dick came up with a much cheaper procedure: based on the identification number, the customer can easily find out from pharmacies what drugs the person in question has bought in the last year and a half, from which the program itself can deduce what kind of disease he suffers from and what his health status is.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol-lowering medication, this indicates that he has virtually uncontrollably high blood fat levels, which immediately places him in a higher-risk category.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some of which determine the risk coefficient at the same time, so the insurance company has almost no work left to do apart from the paperwork, although minor difficulties arise.
Disadvantages include that some drugs can be used for several purposes, for example, some compounds are useful against migraines or hot flushes, but are also effective against depression.
From the point of view of commercial insurance companies, these represent a significant risk-increasing factor, whereas the first-mentioned problems do not.
In order to request and process the data, special companies have been created that ask the patient for permission before obtaining the necessary information from the pharmacies.
The authorities are now forcing them to do this, although they have not punished them for their previous negligence.
Recently, some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory examinations, which they combine with data on the drugs used, thanks to which they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, and at the same time, it will become increasingly difficult to control their use.
There is a special law for the protection of health data, but its effectiveness only applies to health service providers and insurance companies.
A bill that would give authorities the power to audit even businesses that specialize in providing data is before Congress.
Richard Dick recognizes that this is not enough: that is why he has developed his program in such a way that the transfer of data is tied to the express consent of the person concerned.
Another thing is that the person in question can hardly refuse permission, otherwise the insurance companies will not conclude a contract with him.
So the hens are somewhat dependent on the fox&#39;s goodwill after all.
