&quot;From the scientific findings - the leader continues - there is a clear risk and there is a need to react quickly.
The most important thing is that we need to encourage consumers and get this information out there.
We must continue to reexamine existing control systems in light of this scientific finding so that they become fully effective and keep pace with new technology.&quot;
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to investigate the issue, given the high use of portable music devices and the increasing number of young people exposed to noise of this origin.
&quot;Scientists - concluded the executive officer of the EU - confirm that there is a need to be worried and now the European Commission will examine, together with other members and parties that have raised the issue, what measures could possibly be introduced to better protect children and young people from exposure noise caused by portable musical instruments and similar devices&quot;.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100dB, but there are growing concerns about hearing damage that can be caused by overexposure to similar forms of noise.
It is possible to greatly reduce these damages by looking for solutions such as reducing the level and duration of exposure.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee states that users of portable music devices, if they use loud music (more than 89 decibels) for just five hours a week, exceed the currently valid limits corresponding to the maximum permissible noise in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for an extended period of time risk permanent hearing loss after five years.
This problem should concern 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be calculated between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
