Elites in danger
This phenomenon was already evident a few days ago when the House of Representatives voted against the $700 billion bailout plan presented by the White House: a significant portion of Americans were and are more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is also confirmed by yesterday&#39;s New York Times, which informs us that the current crisis is splitting the Republican Party, which is increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, more moderate, friendly to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, which is, on the contrary, conservative, hostile against &quot;those from Washington&quot; and against the world of finance, especially strong in the states in the middle part and in the south..
The soul that arrogantly manifested itself with the vote I spoke of at the beginning..
However, this thing just quoted is just an example of the changes, the big changes, which the current economic earthquake is already showing: not only in the United States, but in the entire West, and perhaps not only here.
In both the US and Europe, this crisis seems to be acting as an accelerator of long-incubating phenomena that are intensifying in the new climate and finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the reactualization, the extraordinary revival of the market, the dual category of State-power in relation to a certain renationalization of the economy.
The crisis is indeed a crisis of banking and financial institutions, which of course have strong ties abroad, but in which the budgets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state, are included to the greatest extent.
Which created at the same time a political problem for those who run it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people and families who are, among other things, voters.
In short, the crisis appears to be economically global, but politically almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be largely out of the game or to have nothing much to add: the obvious proof was given by the European Union, which is divided as always between different interests and different state strategies and which cannot decide on a common political line.
And so everyone is waiting for the intervention of the government of each individual state, rescue plans, market recovery, new rules and, above all, the distribution of funds: the moment we get into trouble, only the states have the economic means, the amount of financial resources, to be able to try to put everything into ok
And they also possess the necessary means and authority to use them: two resources of immense value, under certain circumstances, which perhaps no market and no international organization will ever be able to command to a similar degree.
This new emphasis, which the crisis places on the state-national element, is, after all, in complete harmony with the ever-increasing importance which attempts to attribute recent economic progress to one factor closely connected with it: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had entered the kingdom of networks, increasingly sophisticated technology, immaterial, while we were convinced that global finance was already destined to rule the world, we suddenly realized that our future would have to be the opposite to deal more and more with such little intangible things as water, grain, diesel.
All things, who would have said it, can be transported from one place on earth to another, but in each case they are connected, absolutely, to a bounded space, a territory.
So, whoever becomes their ruler certainly has a lot more cards up his sleeve than whoever isn&#39;t, and whoever has the misfortune of living in a place with no grain, no diesel, and no water.
I come to the second piece of news, which, however, predicts a turning point.
Whoever talks about the territory, the state, the government, inevitably talks about politics, that is, about leadership.
Taking into account the economic crisis, two convergent phenomena seem to be forming.
On the one hand, the realization that there is an objective need for authoritative leadership, a request for someone who could take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit towards the existing leaderships, especially the economic ones, which turned out to be equally unsatisfactory and full of dark places.
And together something even deeper and in a certain sense disturbing: the discredit, the impatience, the sense of incompetence and absence that tries to dominate the entire ruling class in more and more Western countries.
For it seems that the belief is spreading more and more among the broad masses of the population, rather than their actions being the same as the thoughts of the hitherto popular elite, as their way of feeling and being, as their culture in the true sense of the word, that the elite have already outgrown their time and are indifferent to the opinions of the majority.
In short, the demand for leadership feeds one branch from underground, but the strong movement to eliminate the ruling classes and the traditional political order manifests itself in sudden electoral &quot;revolts&quot; or in unexpected changes in collective moods in recent and most recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the fall of Labor in Great Britain, to the revolt of American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy has something to do with it).
We have the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their ceremonies, their newspapers, their accredited intelligentsia, some would say their format, have more and more problems understanding, i.e. representing, which, not from today, is created in deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis is re-invigorating, expanding, potentially over-exaggerating.
Before this, it would be an exaggeration to talk about a permanent &quot;mass revolt&quot;.
But we certainly can&#39;t say that it means keeping your eyes wide open.
