Students victims of expensive rents - up to 900 euros per room
The rental market for university students knows no crisis.
According to the latest research by Sunio, the tenants&#39; union, renting a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
&quot;The phenomenon has already reached such proportions that whole classes of students have lost the right to study because of the overall too high prices that their families would have to bear - explains the head of the office for Sunia studies, Laura Mariani - in this city, the high demand from students has distorted the market in such a way that it stimulated the process of price increases, which also spread to residents&quot;.
In most cases, rental offers contain several violations: open contracts, unregistered, no limited rent, associated subleases.
An exceptional intervention is needed for Sunji, which could regulate prices through a tax overhaul.
If we look at the details of the research, we will see that in Milan, in the Brianza area, about 450 euro is needed for a single bed, for a single room you pay from a minimum price of 650 (Zone Bande Nere) to an average value of 800 (Zone Lambiate, Udine and Fiera) up to a maximum of 900 (in the Vittoria zone).
In Florence, one bed costs on average 350/400 euros, one room about 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in zones close to the university, 250/280 euros are needed for a bed in a double room, from 370 to 500 in a single room.
In Rome in the central university zones (San Lorenzo, piazza Bologna) they want roughly 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a double bed.
Prices are a little lower (550 euros for a single bed) in zones close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
We save only if we move to the peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed and 450 for a single room in the zones of Prenestina, Centocelle and the like.
In Naples, a bed costs about 300/450 euros, a room from 400 to 600 euros, with the highest prices in the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei zones.
In Bari they want 250/350 euro for a bed, at least 350 for a single room.
In smaller cities, prices are definitely lower, but they have a greater impact on the economy of citizens.
In cities like Perugia, where the most common phenomenon is rent for students from countries outside the European Union, one more anomaly is finally noticed: an increase of about 25-30% of the fee they want for foreign students compared to Italian ones.
Goodbye to the old Paradiso cinema, cities are canceling historic theaters
Historical cinema theaters are closing in favor of the Multiplex.
&quot;A city without cinemas is like a blind person, it&#39;s like a face without eyes.&quot;
The picture offered by the director Giuseppe Tornator successfully documents what is happening in the big Italian urban centers, but also in the country towns.
The process of limiting cinemas, the birth of large multiplexes in the suburbs and the subsequent demise of monoscreens in the central zones of cities, is one of the events that seems inevitable and irreversible, but it also has all the signs of a real cultural crime.
Historical places full of memories often disappear, &quot;it&#39;s like losing a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared part of the journey and a lot of emotions&quot;, feels the director of the New Cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won Tornator an Oscar and a grand jury prize in Cannes, and which told the poetry of a village cinema and the sadness of a way of life that cinema has probably lost forever.
The values obtained by Anec, the main association of operators, speak clearly: in the last five years, 316 cinemas of the traditional tip have closed their doors, and the highest bill was paid mainly by theaters in the most important cities: by 10 less in Florence, by 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, by 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by closures, Emilia-Romagna is in first place with the loss of 82 cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And the proof that the first responsible for their disappearance is the arrival of the multiplex are precisely these three Italian regions that registered the highest number of new cinema multiplexes: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna .
«The Italian procedure has developed irrationally», says Paolo Protti, president of Anec, &quot;it is useful to create new structures, but it would be necessary to guarantee that the existing ones will survive, because if one cinema in the city closes, not all its visitors are willing to move to multiplex.
Then let&#39;s not even talk about the insufficient subsidy for the fund in favor of the operators: the previous state debt is roughly 10 million euros.
From a moral and ethical point of view, it is a shame that the government does not respect existing laws.
Between 16 and 18 million euros per year would be needed to support the sector».
The case of Bologna is interesting, the first Italian city to be concerned about closures and which decided to find a way out by signing a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to protect and promote small cinemas both in historic centers and in the suburbs.
Among the planned norms are steps in tax relief in favor of operators and benefits for the audience in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the zone with limited traffic and will have special prices for stopping and in some car parks.
«I like this initiative» says Giuseppe Tornatore&quot;and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by introducing other measures».
However, it is certain that in order to stand up to the might of the multiplex, traditional theaters need to improve their sound and image quality, as today&#39;s audiences are more demanding.
The defense of the traditional cinema is a topic that has always been important: the closing of the Super Cinema in Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to found the &quot;New Cinema Paradiso&quot;, which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the already closed Rialto or Quirinal in Via Nazionale, where I shared so many emotions so that I don&#39;t have to look at the inscriptions blackened by dust, I turn the other way».
